<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The tobacco settlement appears to all but dead, and the
momentum for a tobacco bill this year is slipping away. President
Clinton is expected to announce soon whether he wants to continue
the path begun three months ago or start anew.
</P>
<P>
-- As affluent buyers become more willing to pay more for
comfort and convenience, manufacturers are increasingly adding
features that push their products into the high end of the market.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- India paid final tribute to Mother Teresa Saturday with a
state funeral and laid the Nobel Prize-winning nun to rest inside
the international headquarters of the Catholic mission she founded
in this city's slums half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton urges Congress to overhaul campaign
finance laws, saying the system for paying for campaigns is
broken.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Publisher Steve Forbes, no longer the single issue guru of
the flat tax, wowed more than 2,000 Christian Coalition members
here Saturday in a day filled with speeches by possible Republican
nomination hopefuls for 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
