<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Blessed With Opportunities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region is to rank itself among China's richest provinces next
century, thanks to its superior resources as well as the central
government's policy favoring the development of the western parts
of the country, said a Xinjiang official here today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Lequan, a delegate to the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China, which opened here on Friday, quoted
Jiang Zemin's report at the opening session of the congress as
saying that the government will enhance its support to the middle
and west regions, and that priority will be given to
infrastructural construction and resources exploitation in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"Xinjiang benefits much from the state policy which is
preferential to developing the country's central and west
regions," said Wang, secretary of the Xinjiang regional Party
committee.
</P>
<P>
The country has allocated a total of nearly 50 billion yuan to
tap its rich petroleum resources. So far over ten oil-fields have
been developed with a total production capacity of 17 million tons
of crude oil per year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 39 major chemical projects with a total investment of
over 30 billion yuan are being built in Xinjiang, including an
ethylene plant with an annual capacity of 140,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang, the largest cotton producer in the country, vows to
turn the region into the nation's largest cotton spinning base
with an annual capacity of three million spindles, as well as a
super-large base for commercial cotton with annual production
expected to reach 1.5 billion kilograms.
</P>
<P>
"Xinjiang has explored the potential markets of central Asian
countries along the border and taken advantage of the second
Asian-European continental bridge, that passes through it, to
carry out economic cooperation with foreign countries," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Covering one sixth of the country's total area, Xinjiang
borders eight countries, from India to the south to Mongolia to
the north.
</P>
<P>
"Xinjiang is shaping an export-oriented economic structure with
main focus on these bordering countries," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang boasts the country's richest resources in 29 areas,
including petroleum, coal and natural gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
