<HEADLINE> German Army Plane Crash, 24 Feared Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A German army plane has crashed
into the Atlantic Ocean off the Angola coast, probably claiming
the lives of all 24 people aboard, German Defense Minister Volker
Ruehe said here today.
</P>
<P>
"There is no hope of any survivors," Ruehe said in a news
conference here.
</P>
<P>
The Soviet-made Tupolev 154 was en route from Germany to Cape
Town in South Africa for ceremonies marking the 75th anniversary
of the South African navy.
</P>
<P>
The last radio signal received from the plane was registered
late Saturday when it was about 1,500 kilometers west of Angola.
</P>
<P>
Because no emergency signals had been sent, there was great
uncertainty over where the plane went down exactly, Ruehe said.
</P>
<P>
The search conducted by a French military aircraft and a
British plane had been fruitless so far, but another massive
search operation would be launched, he added.
</P>
<P>
Those on board were 12 German navy soldiers, 10 flight crew
members and wives of two of them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
