<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Develops National Tourism Master Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean cabinet minister
said the government is developing a national tourism master plan
as an effort to promote the growing sector.
</P>
<P>
Mines, environment and tourism minister Simon Moyo said on
Sunday the master plan would, among other things, enhance
environmental management to ensure the protection of the
environment for the benefit of future generations.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry is also working on facilitating the realisation
of continued investment in the tourist sector in view of the fact
that there is yet untapped potential, especially in most of our
rural areas where safari tourism can take advantage of the
wildlife resource and scenery management benefits accruing from
the communal areas management programme for indigenous resources
(campfire)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Environmental experts believe that growth of tourism has
caused major ecological problems particularly in areas like
Victoria Falls, the country's premier tourist resort.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has in recent years grown to become one of the major
sectors in Zimbabwe, with receipts as a percentage of gross
domestic product increasing from 2.6 percent in 1990 to 4.6
percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Moyo added Zimbabwe hosts a regional investment forum in
October this year which is expected to draw tourism experts from
the Southern African Development Community.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was supportive of joint venture
investments between indigenous people and foreign investors and
had put in place a number of incentives to promote development of
the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
