<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Millennium Bomb" to Hit High Street Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Shoppers all over the world
could be hit by the so-called "Millennium Bomb" next month as the
first bank and credit cards are issued with expiry dates in 2000.
</P>
<P>
It is increasingly accepted that the bug, the result of the
date change from 1999 to 2000, will affect millions of ordinary
consumers, as well as computer users.
</P>
<P>
Stores and restaurants are bracing themselves for the
possibility that thousands of customers will be unable to pay,
because terminals will refuse to accept cards bearing an "00" date
unless they have been reprogramed.
</P>
<P>
It was reported the first cards will be issued in October,
after a year's delay as banks and retailers have tried to ensure
there will be no problems.
</P>
<P>
Many computers recognize the year by its last two digits, for
example, 97 for 1997.
</P>
<P>
When the date reaches 00, millions of computers worldwide will
believe the year is 1900, causing widespread chaos unless they are
reprogramed.
</P>
<P>
Visa and Mastercard, the two biggest credit card schemes, were
reported to have reprogramed more than 3.5 million terminals and
cash machines throughout Europe. But problems may still arise.
</P>
<P>
Some models of microwave oven and VCR recorder with calendars
are vulnerable to failure because of the date change and there are
fears that televisions, washing machines and toasters could also
go wrong.
</P>
<P>
A lawyer specializing in "Year 2000" issues, said, "Nobody
knows how bad it will be. I am expecting a lot of legal action."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
