<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Land Policy to Benefit Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Zimbabwean
National Land Acquisition and Minister Without Portfolio Joseph
Msika has said large estates like the Lowveld Sugar Estates,
Eastern Highlands Timber, tea and coffee plantations will be
spared from the compulsory land designation exercise.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Land Acquisition Committee in Matabeleland
south Sunday, Msika said the estates contributed immensely to the
country's agro-based economy and should not be disturbed just for
the sake of it.
</P>
<P>
"The land redistribution exercise should not be taken
emotionally, because if everyone cries to be resettled anywhere,
there is a danger that we are killing the economy," he said,
challenging blacks who wanted to take over white-owned commercial
farms to be prepared to equal or better their former owners.
</P>
<P>
He said whites should not view the exercise as racism in
reverse as the government was only trying to resolve the land
imbalance created by decades of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate that the few whites who own most of the
productive land are contributing greatly to the national economy,
but 17 years after independence it is unacceptable that a
majority of people are still landless after fighting a brutal war
of liberation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The government is not going to take all the farms owned by
white people, but will only enforce the new concept of one person
one farm to ensure that no one monopolises the land," he said,
adding only in very special cases would an individual be allowed
to own a maximum of two farms.
</P>
<P>
The National Land Acquisition Committee recently identified a
total of 1,772 commercial farms countrywide, covering over 4.6
million hectares to resettle the landless peasants.
</P>
<P>
During the past 17 years, the government resettled some 70,000
people with financial assistance from Britain, which was later
withdrawn citing mismanagement of the land resettlement program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
