<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait, Philippines Sign Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait and the
Philippines have signed two agreements on trade and cultural
cooperation, visiting Philippine President Fidel Ramos said today.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at a news conference that three memorandums
of understanding to promote consultations between their foreign
ministries, labor and manpower development, and reciprocal
investments were also signed today.
</P>
<P>
During the past two days, the first Philippine president ever
to visit Kuwait held discussions with Kuwaiti leaders on ways to
remove obstacles to bilateral trade, which has been shrinking in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 Kuwaiti-Philippine trade slid to only 34 million
U.S. dollars compared with 202.4 million in 1992. Ramos said he
saw a big potential of economic and trade exchanges between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
On the memo to facilitate labor and manpower development, the
president hoped that more opportunities would be created for
technical and professional Filipinos to work in Kuwait. The
oil-rich Gulf state now hosts 60,000 Filipinos mainly working as
house maids.
</P>
<P>
Ramos expressed the belief that through his visit to Kuwait,
bilateral relations would be further strengthened and trade and
investment opportunities generated for both Kuwait and his
country.
</P>
<P>
This afternoon, the chambers of commerce and industry of the
two countries were expected to sign a protocol of agreement on
promotion and encouragement of mutual investment between the
private sectors of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ramos arrived here Saturday morning at the second leg of his
four-nation tour which has taken him to Russia, and will take him
to the Czech Republic and Austria. He is expected to leave for
Prague, Czech, early Monday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
