<HEADLINE> Cameroun's Minister of External Relations Attends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Ferdinand Oyono, the
Cameroun's minister of external relations left the country on
September 13 for Libreville, Gabon, to attend the summit on the
Congolese crisis, according to Radio Cameroun today.
</P>
<P>
The summit on the Congolese crisis is expected to be opened in
Libreville today. Oyono is to represent the head of state of
Cameroun president Paul Biya at the summit.
</P>
<P>
Some of the African heads of state including the Republic of
Central Africa's president Ange Patasse, Chadian president Idriss
Deby and Malian leader Alpha Oumar Konare are already in the
Gabonese capital Libreville for talks aimed at seeking solutions
to the Congolese crisis.
</P>
<P>
The summit will be chaired by Gabonese president Omar Bongo
who is also the chairman of the international mediation committee
of the Congolese crisis.
</P>
<P>
Since fighting started on June 5 between the forces loyal to
Congolese president Pascal Lissouba and those of his rival former
president Sassou Nguesso, both national and international
mediation committees have been making efforts to bring an end to
the fight in the country.
</P>
<P>
Five peace plans have been initiated by Gabonese president Bongo.
</P>
</TEXT>
