<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Foreign Ministers Meet in Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
six Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states met in southern Saudi
resort city of Abha today mainly to discuss issues of improving
relations with Iran, the Middle East peace process and regional
security.
</P>
<P>
Reports by Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) from Abha said that
Chairman of the 64th GCC ministerial meeting, Qatari Foreign
Minister Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassem Al-Thani expressed the hope at
the inaugural session that relations between the GCC and Iran
would develop in the future.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and GCC states Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Oman and Bahrain developed
considerably over the past few years and took a positive
turn with the election of moderate Mohamad Khatami as new
Iranian president.
</P>
<P>
Kuna said the ministers would also discuss economic and
environmental issues, and the unifying customs tariffs which has
so far covered 94.5 percent of the total goods in GCC states will
also be emerged in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting started after the ministers held talks with
visiting State Secretary of the United States of America
Madeleine Albright earlier today during which the ministers
welcomed her efforts to revive the Middle East peace process
while Albright urged the GCC states to take part in the Doha
Economic Summit of the Middle East and North Africa scheduled to
be held in November.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will conclude their meeting Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
