<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Hopes GCC Members to Attend Doha Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today expressed the hope that all the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) member states will attend the 4th
Middle East and North Africa economic summit to be held in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
She made the remark while meeting foreign ministers of the
GCC states in the southern Saudi resort city of Abha, Kuwait News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"I want to reiterate strongly our hope that members of the
council will participate in this year's Middle East and North
Africa Summit, which the government of Qatar was graciously
agreed to host," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
She added "the efforts to increase regional economic
cooperation is not, as see to suggest, a kind of concession to
Israel. It is a vital underpinning to the long term prospects for
peace."
</P>
<P>
"The Doha summit is another opportunity to convey a message
to the world that the Middle East can be a source of economic
dynamism and opportunity and that the Gulf states are active in
diversifying their own interests and building regional
prosperity," the U.S. secretary of state noted.
</P>
<P>
GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates
(UAE), Qatar, Oman and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Ben Jassem Bin
Jaber al Thani today affirmed at the meeting his country's
resolve to hold the controversial summit, saying the meeting will
be held in November as scheduled despite difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and the UAE had announced their intention to
boycott the summit due to Israel's participation. So far, Kuwait,
Bahrain and Oman have not publicly expressed their attitudes to
the summit yet.
</P>
<P>
But Gulf diplomats said Kuwait and Bahrain also favor a
boycott, while Oman plans to attend the summit due to be
held in the Qatari capital Doha.
</P>
<P>
Albright is currently on a Mideast tour, which includes
Israel, Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria, Egypt, Saudi
Arabia, and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Her maiden trip to the region aimed at reviving the stalled
Mideast peace process that came to a halt since Israel began
construction of a new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in
March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
