<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Interior Ministry OKs Controversial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Interior Ministry
today cleared the way for a highly controversial Jewish
housing project in East Jerusalem's Ras Amud Arab neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's Construction Appeal Committee rejected an appeal
against the project filed by two council members of the
Jerusalem Municipality, who argued that the building permit was
not legally issued and the project would have disastrous
political ramifications if carried out.
</P>
<P>
But the committee ruled today that the permit to the American
millionaire buyer Irwing Moscowitz was issued legally by a
sub-committee of the municipality, adding that it had no
authorization to examine the political ramifications of the
project.
</P>
<P>
Moscowitz, with the full backing from the hawkish Jerusalem
Mayor Ehud Olmert, hoped to build 70 housings for Jews in
the mostly Arab neighborhood Ras Amud, which is near the
Mount of Olives.
</P>
<P>
In late July after the Jerusalem Municipality issued the
permit to start the construction, a political and diplomatic
uproar erupted over the danger of going ahead with such
controversial plan.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Arab countries sternly warned that the
housing plan would lead to new violence and collapse of the
peace process which has been halted since Israel began in
March building the Har Homa settlement in southeastern
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
And Israeli opposition Labor party warned that the start of
Ras Amud project could cause a disaster reminiscent of the
bloodshed between Israel and the Palestinians after the opening
of an underground archaeological tunnel in East Jerusalem last
September.
</P>
<P>
Under the political pressure, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
later promised that the government would not allow the project
to begin. Israeli government informed the United States, Egypt
and Jordan of its decision made in a Cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ornan Yehutieli, one of the two council members who
appealed the permission to Moscowitz, said today that he
believed Olmert and Moscowitz would soon press ahead with the
housing project since the last hurdle was cleared.
</P>
<P>
He blasted Olmert and Moscowitz for trying to ignite a
widespread confrontation between Israelis and Palestinians, citing
that the project is not a solution to Jewish housing problem
whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
"I think that as soon as the time is possible, they
will find the way because this is the button they have to
press in order to light a big fire in Jerusalem," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yehutieli said that he had appealed to the Jerusalem
District Court in the last attempt to block the dangerous
project. The court is expected to hear his appeal in the
next few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
