<HEADLINE> Reporters Found Guilty of Libeling Mubarak's Sons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A Cairo court today sentenced
five reporters to a suspended one-year prison term for libeling
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's sons in a high-profile suit
against two Saudi publications.
</P>
<P>
The reporters, three Saudis and two Egyptians, were tried in
absentia and each was fined 20,000 Egyptian pounds and ordered to
pay a bail of 1,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
The court sentenced a sixth reporter, an Egyptian man who
appeared on court, to six years in prison and a fine of 1,500
pounds.
</P>
<P>
The court also ordered all the defendants to pay 501 pounds
(125 dollars) as temporary compensation to their suers and repay
all litigation costs.
</P>
<P>
Alaa and Gamal Mubarak charged the journalists on July 12 for
an article that accused them of peddling their father's influence
to explore their own benefits.
</P>
<P>
Ashraq Al Awsat daily, part of the Saudi publishing group of
the same name, published on May 27 an advertisement for its sister
weekly magazine Al Jadida containing an article implicating
Mubarak's sons in illegal business dealings.
</P>
<P>
The article, which was written for the Arabic daily and
advertised by its sister magazine, in fact never appeared and two
of the weekly's editors were sacked.
</P>
<P>
The publishers, who had apologized for the "wrongdoing" and
asked for leniency and forgiveness of Mubarak's sons, said they
confiscated all issues of the magazine before they reached the
newsstands.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's two sons, who are both prominent members of Egyptian
business groups, said the ad "included lies defaming their
characters and the reputation of their family." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
