<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> San Francisco Transit Trains to Run Again as Strike Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Transit train workers in
San Francisco are expected to go back to work Monday after a
week-long strike to demand higher wages.
</P>
<P>
A tentative 43.5 million dollar agreement was reached Saturday
between the Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART) management and striking
unions. The breakthrough came during negotiations when the BART
agreed to offer a four-year contract instead of the three-year
contract it had with its unions.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, each of the BART's 2,600 employees
will be given a lump-sum payment in the first year and a 4 percent
wage increase annually for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
It was a compromise for both sides. The unions had sought
annual raises of respective 6.5, 5.5 and 5 percent for the next
three years, while the management insisted on an annual 3 percent
pay raise.
</P>
<P>
The BART normally carries about 275,000 riders daily on 93
miles of track that connect San Francisco and East Bay bedroom
communities. During the strike commuters had to switch to ferries,
buses, car pools and telecommuting and cope with endless traffic
jams.
</P>
<P>
Public opinion played a role in bringing in the agreement.
Throughout the week, the Bay Area residents expressed anger at
both the management and unions for disputing their lives. Some
said the disputing sides cared no public interests. The BART
employees are actually the highest-paid public transit workers in
the state and face no threat of replacement, while most of the
BART income comes from taxes and subsidies, they noted.
</P>
<P>
A local economist said when the negotiations were still going
on that the only real leverage was public opinion.
</P>
<P>
The management and labor were now confident that the public's
anger would dissipate once the trains start running again,
although many angry commuters had vowed that they would not return
to the BART. In fact, the BART customers have no other options.
Most commuters will have to return to the system.
</P>
<P>
The BART's longest strike took place in 1979 which lasted three
months. Its briefest walkout in 1991 lasted only 75 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
