<HEADLINE> Israeli Troop Pullback from Lebanon Called for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Public Security
Minister Avigdor Kalahani today asked for withdrawal of Israeli
troops from south Lebanon to avoid further losses there, Israeli
Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the radio, Kalahani said at today's Cabinet
meeting that Israel should withdraw its forces from Lebanon and
replace them with a multinational force.
</P>
<P>
Israel can reach some sort of agreements with the Iran-backed
Hezbollah (Party of God) militia of Lebanon, which has been
fighting to oust the Israeli occupation, on troop withdrawal and
other security issues along the border, he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kalahani comes from the Third-way Party. The recent killing of
11 Israeli commandos in Lebanon has prompted fierce debate over
whether Israel should withdraw its troops or change its tactics.
</P>
<P>
Israeli military brass, including Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, opposed troops pulling out of Lebanon for fear of a
unilateral withdrawal would lead to an increase in bloodshed when
northern Israel is exposed to attacks from Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
However, Kalahani said, Israel could continue to sustain losses
as long as its troops station in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a security zone 10-15 kilometer wide in south
Lebanon along its border in 1985. Since then, about 300 Israeli
servicemen have been killed in military clashes with Hezbollah in
south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
