<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Says Only Small Steps Achieved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright here tonight admitted only small steps were
accomplished during her week-long trip to the region with the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations to be reactivated at double
levels.
</P>
<P>
Big steps were needed, but small steps were better than no
steps, Albright emphasized during a joint press conference with
Jordan's King Hussein. She said Israel and Palestine agreed to
start top leader-level talks in Washington and minister-level
talks in New York at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The talks at double levels were set up amid crisis of
confidence and might bring new hopes for the Middle East peace
process, said the top U.S. diplomat, who will conclude her trip
right here in Amman after visiting Israel, the Palestinian
self-rule areas, Syria, Egypt and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Albright called on Israel to refrain from
unilateral actions and the Palestinians to crack down on Islamic
terrorist actions in response to Israeli demands.
</P>
<P>
Both Israel and the Palestinians needed to make "hard but
necessary decisions" to reactivate the peace talks, Albright said.
</P>
<P>
Albright described her trip as "exceptionally good" and said
that the U.S. would continue to work very hard to revive the
peace process at an overall level.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decided to do so because it cherished very important
strategic interests in the region, said the secretary of state,
who arrived here this evening and immediately held the press
conference after a brief meeting with King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
She added that she would report about the trip to U.S.
President Bill Clinton whose interests here was "unparallel."
</P>
<P>
Albright had apparently failed to bridge the gap between
Israeli security demands and Palestinian request for a halt in
Jewish settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
Her only success was in cobbling together a renewal of
high-level talks between the two sides later this month in the
U.S. in a bid to tackle their formidable differences.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat are scheduled to meet in Washington while
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Palestinian chief
negotiator Mohammoud Abbas to meet in New York.
</P>
<P>
During the talks late Friday in Damascus with Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad, Albright also failed to return Syria and Israel to
negotiations in order to end the 18-month freeze in their peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Saturday, Albright failed to get an Egyptian commitment for a
high-level participation at a regional economic summit set to
take place in Doha, Qatar in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
This morning, her efforts to persuade six Gulf Cooperation
Council countries to attend the Qatar meeting also turned out no
results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
