<HEADLINE> Israel to Cut Off Aid from Abroad to Hamas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet today
discussed the issue of cutting off aid from abroad to Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas), Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
After the weekly Cabinet meeting, David Bar-Ilan, Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's communication advisor, said it was
still up to the discretion of the prime minister, Foreign
Minister David Levy and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
whether to actually act on the cabinet proposal.
</P>
<P>
"One of the ways to fight the infrastructure of terrorism
organizations is to deprive its funds which make its function
possible," Bar-Ilan said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "it is important to be able to do that especially
when most of the funding for the Hamas functions has gone from
western countries rather than as most people believe from Iran."
But he would not specify which organizations in western countries
were involved.
</P>
<P>
In coincidence, the U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
who was visiting Saudi Arabia, today also urged Gulf states to do
everything possibler to deny financial aid to Hamas and other
radical Islamic groups which sabotage the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hamas, the main militant group opposed to peace agreement
between Israel and Palestinian National Authority (PNA), has claimed
responsibility for most of the suicide bombing attacks against
Israel in years.
</P>
<P>
Israel has urged the PNA to fulfill promises to crack down
on the infrastructure of Hamas and other militant groups in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
