<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese President Reiterates Commitment to IGADD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
Al-Bashir today reiterated his country's commitment to the IGADD's
(Inter-Governmental Authority on Drought and Development for
central and east Africa) initiative.
</P>
<P>
Bashir made this statement during a meeting with IGADD
Executive Secretary Tiksiti Qabri, who arrived here Saturday
on a four-day visit to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
IGADD, which embraces Sudan, Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia,
Eritrea, Somalia and Djibouti, has played a mediatory role between
the Sudanese government and John Garang, leader of the mainstream
rebel group in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
During the summit of IGADD which was held in July in the Kenyan
capital of Nairobi, the Sudanese delegation accepted the IGADD's
declaration of principles of 1994 for resolving the southern Sudan
question.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government had earlier rejected the declaration of
principles which call for separating religion from politics and
upholding political pluralism in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, the visiting IGADD executive secretary
said he expected an IGADD summit would be held soon with the
participation of John Garang to examine the peace effort in
southern Sudan, but no date had been fixed yet, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sudanese Minister of Foreign Affairs Ali Osman
Mohammed Taha Saturday had a meeting with the IGADD executive
secretary on continental integration through the African economic
community. He underlined Sudan's commitment to regional
cooperation in the best interest of the peoples of the region.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese minister Taha also briefed the IGADD official on Sudan's
effort together with South Africa for the establishment of peace
in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Sudan had requested South Africa's President Nelson Mandela
to play the role of mediator between the Sudan, Uganda and the
Garang-led rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
A meeting had actually taken place last month in South Africa
between Bashir and his Uganda counterpart Yoweri Museveni, but
Garang failed to attend, refusing to negotiate with the Sudanese
government delegation.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's rebels in the south have fought the government since
1983, seeking a greater say in Sudan's affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
