<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA, Syrian Presidents to Visit Egypt Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad
and Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat will
visit Egypt this week to discuss the Mideast peace process in the
wake of the recent U.S. peace-saving attempt.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak will meet in the
south Mediterranean port of Alexandria tomorrow to evaluate the
situation following U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's
visit, according to the Middle East News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
Albright's first trip to the region since she took office in
January began on September 10 and has taken her to Israel, the
Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Mubarak talks will see to means of confronting the
Israeli punitive measures imposed on the Palestinians after a
series of suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Al-Assad will exchange views on Thursday regarding
means of rescuing the faltering Mideast peace process, according
to MENA.
</P>
<P>
Syria and the PNA were the second and third stops of Albright's
tour, which failed to score major achievements in easing tensions
and relaunching the peace march on both tracks.
</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli negotiations were frozen since March last
year. The Israeli government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
refused to commit to the promises of its Labor predecessor to
return the Golan Heights it seized from Syria in 1967 in exchange
for peace with the neighbor.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks stalled in March over a new
Jewish settlement project in traditional Arab East Jerusalem,
which the Palestinians want as their future capital. The string of
suicide bombings in Jerusalem in the past five weeks has fueled
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who met Albright in Alexandria on Saturday, praised
her mission in the region as "balanced, promising and
encouraging." Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa called Arafat
Saturday night to brief him on Mubarak-Albright talks.
</P>
<P>
Albright told an Egyptian TV today that she made only minor
steps in easing the crisis of confidence between the Palestinians
and Israelis, affirming that the agreements reached in Oslo are
the foundations of the Mideast peace process and could not be
given up.
</P>
<P>
The Oslo agreements signed four years ago and the historic
handshake between Arafat and late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin in Washington started the Middle East peace process which
has been deadlocked due to Netanyahu government's policies on
issues like Jewish settlement expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
