<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Promises to Continue Aid for Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright pledged here today that the U.S. will continue
its aid to Jordan in appreciation of Jordan's special role in the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
During a joint press conference with King Hussein of Jordan,
Albright said the U.S. government would like to help Jordan keep
its prosperity by continuously channeling aid and grants to the
kingdom in a bid to strengthen the partnership between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. cherished its partnership with the kingdom very much
and hoped to maintain its leadership in the region through keeping
its partnership with Jordan, said the U.S. secretary of state, who
is on the last leg of her Mideast tour which has taken her to
Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria, Egypt and Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has become the 6th largest country in the world in
receiving U.S. aid. Over the past seven years, the U.S. granted
altogether some 1.5 billion U.S. dollars to Jordan in the form of
economic and military aid and debt write-off.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, Jordan has received some 200 million dollars
in aid from Washington. Meanwhile, the U.S. Congress was
reportedly trying to increase this year's aid to Jordan to 250
million dollars despite of its overall plan to cut down on
foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Jordan contributed to the peace process by mediating the
Hebron accord between Israel and the Palestinians in January this
year, under which Israel promised to evacuate some areas in the West
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
