<HEADLINE> African Leaders Meet on Congolese Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Heads of state from west and
central African countries have begun in Gabonese capital
Libreville to discuss ways of resolving the conflict in Congo,
sources monitored said here today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is chaired by Gabonese President Omar Bongo who is
also the chairman of the International Mediation Committee of
Congolese crisis.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of Chad, Senegal, Benin, Togo, Mali, the Republic of
Central Africa and the minister of external relations of Cameroun
as well as special envoy Mohammed Sahnoun of the United Nations
and representative of the Organization of African Unity attended
today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Congo's President Pascal Lissouba is not attending the
meeting. He is represented by Prime Minister Bernard Kolelas.
Former Congolese President Denis Sassou Nguesso is present at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Gabonese President Bongo opened the meeting at noon.
</P>
<P>
Reports say Kolelas and Sassou were received in audience
respectively by the heads of state from the west and central
African nations this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Brazzaville say fighting which has been lasting
for more than three months is still continuing between forces
loyal to President Lissouba and those of his rival Sassou.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
