<HEADLINE> Britain Urged to Provide More Aid to Montserrat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chief Minister of the
Volcano-stricken Carribbean island of Montserrat called on here
today the British government to step up its efforts to help the
Montserrat people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with Britain's Sky Television early
today, Chief Minister David Brandt said: "I hope to get something
concrete to help us start over again."
</P>
<P>
"It is an amount of money (Montserrat is asking for). Not a
specific sum at this time but there are some things that are
critical. There is the question of housing," he said.
</P>
<P>
Britain has so far pledged an aid package worth 41.5 million
pounds (about 66.4 million U.S. dollars), including another
6.5-million-pound (about 10.4 million dollars) emergency housing
program.
</P>
<P>
Brandt, who was appointed Chief Minister last month after a row
over London's aid package forced his predecessor to quit, arrived
in London on Saturday for crisis talks with British government
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Brandt is expected to meet Prime Minister Tony Blair, Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook and International Development Minister George
Foulkes later today to discuss further British assistance.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a statement that
the British government is "acutely aware of longer term housing
shortage in the North (of the island). We are doing everything to
address this problem and are determined to accelerate this vital
work."
</P>
<P>
"Our commitment to the people of Montserrat is long-term. Our
Sustainable Development Plan will create a lasting and viable
infrastructure in the North of Montseratt," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Montserrat's Southfriere Hills volcano became dramatically
active from July 1995, destroying many places on the tiny island in
eastern Caribbean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
