<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Visitors Make Fewer Trips to Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Visitors from overseas
countries made fewer overnight trips to Canada in July than in
June, the fifth consecutive monthly decrease since last February's
peak.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada reported today that visitors from overseas
countries took 345,000 trips of one or more nights to Canada in
July, down 1.7 percent from June.
</P>
<P>
This was the lowest number of overnight trips to Canada by
overseas visitors since January 1996 and was 15 percent lower than
February's peak.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, most European currencies and the Japanese
yen have lost some value compared with the Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
In July, Americans made more overnight trips to Canada than in
the previous month, up 1.0 percent, according to the statistics
agency.
</P>
<P>
Overall, foreigners took 1.4 million trips to Canada in July,
practically unchanged from June.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Canadians made a near-record number of trips
to overseas destinations.
</P>
<P>
Canadians made 2.0 percent more overseas trips in July than in
June. At 336,000, the number was almost as high as last April's
peak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
