<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Pak PM's Swiss Accounts Frozen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss government has
ordered four Swiss banks to freeze accounts and lockers in the
name of former Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto "on the basis of
solid evidence that the wealth was ill-gotten," a senior official
said.
</P>
<P>
"The freeze order is effective from September 8," Saiful
Rehman, chairman of the Ehtesab (accountability) Cell, told a news
conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Accounts in the names of Benazir's spouse Asif Zardari and
mother Nusrat Bhutto were also frozen, said Rehman, who provided
the Swiss government and banks with the evidence.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss banks and all their branches which froze the
accounts, vaults and lockers of the three will provide details of
all the transactions made since opening of the accounts, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss banks include Union Bank of Switzerland (UBS),
Barclays Bank (Swiss) and S. A. Citi Bank (Switzerland), he said.
</P>
<P>
Rehman recalled that the former prime minister had always
denied the existence of her foreign bank accounts and challenged
that if proved all the wealth amassed may be acquired by the
government.
</P>
<P>
"She will be obliged and the looted money soon be returned to
the national exchequer," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeking assistance of British and French authorities as
well and have identified the banks and account numbers of the
former prime minister and her spouse," he added. He hoped these
accounts would also be frozen.
</P>
<P>
He charged that the "royal couple" made billions overnight by
"underhand deals" and that they tailored rules and regulations and
altered policies and procedures for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
This hectic task (getting the accounts frozen) has been
achieved within 100 days of the cell's coming into operation on
June 1, 1997, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The present government proceeded against the plunderers of
national wealth fully honoring independence of the judiciary and
free press and abiding by the rule of law, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
