<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Textile Exports Up Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' textile
exports reached nearly 2 billion U.S. dollars in the first eight
months of this year, up 7.5 percent from a year ago, official
figures showed today.
</P>
<P>
The slight increase was a result of higher demand from the
United States, a major quota country for Philippine textiles,
according to a report issued by the country's Garments and Textile
Export Board (GTEB).
</P>
<P>
The United States remained the biggest buyer of the country's
textiles, with its payments accounting for 62 percent of the
Philippines' total receipts from textile exports during the
period.
</P>
<P>
The United States purchased 1.23 billion dollars worth of
Philippine textiles during the period, an 11-percent hike from a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Canada, another quota country, also improved at an
impressive rate of 9.7 percent from 37.4 million dollars to 41
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Of the total textile exports, 80 percent were apparel while the
rest were composed of linens and other embroidered household
items. 
</P>
</TEXT>
