<HEADLINE> Britain, Ireland Urge Unionists to Join Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Britain and Ireland issued a
joint statement today to persuade pro-British unionists into
joining the Northern Ireland peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The statement, by Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain and
Bertie Ahern of Ireland, was made in Belfast, of Northern Ireland,
just before the negotiations were due to open.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the two main concerns of the Ulster Unionist Party
(UUP), the two leaders pledged that the people of Northern Ireland
would decide the territory's future and that they wanted
guerrillas to disarm during the talks.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement came hours before the first substantive
plenary session of the year-old peace talks was scheduled to open
in Belfast's Stormont Castle buildings.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the UUP leadership was due to meet to decide whether
or not it would hold direct negotiations with its arch-foe, the
Irish Republican Army's political wing, Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers said Northern Ireland's British status
would not change without the consent of its 1.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
"Consent will be a guiding principle for them in the
negotiations, from which no outcome is of course excluded or
pre-determined," the statement said. 
</P>
