<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Jobless Rate Falls Twice in Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate across
the European Union (EU) fell to 10.7 percent in June and again to
10.6 percent in July, Eurostat said today.
</P>
<P>
The new rates, which were seasonally adjusted, were down from
the 10.8 percent for the first five months of the year, said
Eurostat, the EU's statistical office based in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, average jobless rate in the 15-member EU was
10.9 percent in July 1996 and 10.7 percent in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
As a recent trend, the jobless rate for men fell from 9.5
percent to 9.3 percent while that for women ebbed from 12.6
percent to 12.5 percent over the May-July period this year.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat, which linked the drops to falling rates in the United
Kingdom, the Scandinavian countries, Portugal and Spain, estimated
that a total of 18.0 million people were jobless in the EU in July.
</P>
<P>
However, the encouraging overall trend did not extend to
Germany, where unemployment continued to rise to 9.7 percent,
particularly for young people, whose jobless rate was 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Spain registered the highest unemployment rate of 19.9 percent
among EU members in July, while Luxembourg and Austria had the
lowest ones of 3.8 percent and 4.5 percent respectively, Eurostat
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
