<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE' 1996 Foreign Debt Rises to 10.48b Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) registered a total of 10.84 billion U.S. dollars in foreign
debt by the end of 1996, the local Gulf News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, nearly 9.8 billion dollars, or 90 percent were in
the form of short-term debts while the remaining 1.04 billion
dollars were debt servicing, a report of the Kuwait-based Inter
Arab Investment Guarantee Corp showed.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, foreign debt accounted for 24.8
percent of UAE's gross domestic product (GDP) last year.
</P>
<P>
Figures provided by the UAE Central Bank showed that the
country's deficit in 1996 rose to a record high of 4.82 billion
dollars despite a surge in oil earnings.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank attributed this to a sharp increase in
expenditure an unprecedented 19.48 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The UAE's daily oil output stands at 2.16 million barrels under
a quota agreement with the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries. Crude oil and gas sales account for more than
two-thirds of its total revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
