<HEADLINE> HK Elections Called Stepping Stone to Universal Vote (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The elections in May next
year are a stepping stone that will set Hong Kong firmly on the
road to the universal suffrage envisaged in the Basic Law,
Administrative Secretary of the Special Administrative Region
(SAR) Anson Chan said here today.
</P>
<P>
Delivering her first major speech after the handover at the
American Chamber of Commerce, Chan said it is hardly surprising
that there should have been vigorous debate about the arrangements
for the first Legislative Council elections which have been
announced and are now being discussed throughout the community.
</P>
<P>
"This debate was not only expected; it is perfectly healthy,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
"Various groups in Hong Kong have different views as to whether
our proposals for a combination of proportional representation
for geographic constituencies; corporate voting in our functional
constituencies; and block voting in the election committee is
more or less democratic than other forms of election," she said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that there is no universal truth about the perfect
election, Chan said each society should be allowed to develop its
own process, based on its own particular social, historical,
political and cultural conditions.
</P>
<P>
"I think we could all agree that Hong Kong's social, political
and historical conditions are different from most, if not all;
that a degree of care and attention is required, particularly in
relation to the unique situation embodied in One Country, Two
Systems, and the specific intent and spirit of our constitutional
imperatives, i.e. the requirements of the Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
She quoted Chinese President Jiang Zemin at the inauguration of
the SAR, who said: "A gradually improved democratic system suited
to Hong Kong's reality is an important guarantee for its social
and political stability" and SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa at
the same ceremony: "Democracy is the hallmark of a new era for
Hong Kong."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Elections Called Stepping Stone to Universal Vote (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
She told the audience that the SAR government will launch an
unprecedented effort to enroll a far greater number of eligible
electors and do all it can to ensure that many more people get out
and vote.
</P>
<P>
"We will go all out to try and break previous records. I
believe Hong Kong people will respond to the opportunity -- the
historic opportunity -- to take part in its first democratic
election as part of China," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the elections will be overseen by an independent
electoral commission, which she said "will be an impartial and
apolitical body whose jobs will be to ensure that the election is
not only conducted openly and fairly, but is also seen to be so."
</P>
<P>
According to the administrative secretary, the overall result
would be a balanced legislature representative of the
multi-colored spectrum of opinion and aspirations of the
community.
</P>
<P>
"If we don't live up to that, you will soon hear about it. For
one of the other heartening facts about post-transition Hong Kong
has been the continuing good health of the press."
</P>
<P>
Turning to the importance of the rule of law, Chan said it has
remained resolutely and independently at the heart of Hong Kong's
way of life.
</P>
<P>
"The rule of law is the very essence of Hong Kong's success and
must be protected and preserved by all of us," she said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement reached last week between the Chief Justice of
the SAR and the British Lord Chancellor to make available two of
Britain's Law Lords to serve on the SAR Court of Final Appeal was
"universally applauded for the signal it sent about the
independence of our judiciary and the quality of justice we can
expect in the SAR," she said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on her recent private tour of Shanghai to receive a
professorship, Chan said, "No one who has seen the huge physical
and human progress that is evident everywhere in Shanghai can
doubt that China is moving with the times."
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to being part of an increasingly open,
prosperous and powerful China that will play an increasingly
prominent role on the world stage to the benefit of China and the
rest of the international community," Chan said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
