<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Criticizes Jewish Presence in Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) Middle
East peace envoy Miguel Moratinos today denounced the overnight
occupation of two buildings in East Jerusalem's Arab neighborhood
Ras Amud by three Jewish families.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy,
Moratinos criticized the move by the Jewish radicals as a
"provocation." He expressed the hope that Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's remarks against the planned building in the
neighborhood would also apply to the latest developments.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos, who has met with Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) leader Yasser Arafat and other officials in the past days
following a visit here by United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, is working to resume the deadlocked
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Levy also criticized the action taken by the Jewish families
as "unnecessary and damaging" to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian rioting was sparked Sunday night as soon as
the settlers moved into two empty buildings in the neighborhood,
where the Miami-based American millionaire developer Irving Moscowitz
intends to build 70 housing units for Jews.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian protesters threw stones at the settlers and smashed
their cars before a large number of Israeli police rushed to the
scene to separate the parties.
</P>
<P>
Despite the heavy presence of Israeli police, some Palestinian
youths threw stones at the buildings housing the 15 Jewish adults
and children. And a group of leftist Israeli peace activists held
a demonstration to protest the settlers' move.
</P>
<P>
The settler families denied that they took the action to
damage the visit of Albright here days ago, who demanded
Israel refrain from taking unilateral steps that could scuttle
the chance of resuming the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
They also refuted reports that Netanyahu knew about their plan
to move into Ras Amud, saying he only learned their plan shortly
before they took the action.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a heated debate erupted across Israel's political
spectrum amid huge differences over the settlers' action between
the ruling coalition and the opposition camp.
</P>
<P>
The rightist camp welcomed the action and called on the
government to allow the settlers to continue living in Ras
Amud. Zvi Handel, a lawmaker from the National Religious party,
hailed the action as a proper response to the recent suicide
bombings in Jerusalem launched by Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Tsomet lawmaker Modi Zanberg said that even the government had
to honor the law, especially after it became clear that the entry
to the buildings by the Jewish families was legal. Jerusalem
police has refused to evict the settlers from the buildings which
were legally purchased by Moscowitz.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Labor party's Knesset (Parliament) faction leader
Ranan Cohen condemned the settlers' move and called on Netanyahu
to stop such provocation, citing that it would only encourage
more terrorism and heighten Palestinian frustration.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid also denounced the latest
developments, saying the settlers should be removed from the
neighborhood immediately.
</P>
<P>
Due to the sensitivity of the issue of East Jerusalem,
Israeli government has promised to the Palestinians and Arab
countries that it would not allow the project to be carried
out at the stage. Netanyahu's media adviser David Bar-Illan said
that the prime minister will invoke state security to block
the project.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday incident came right after the Interior Ministry
gave the green light to the project by rejecting a petition
against it filed by two leftist city councillors.
</P>
<P>
Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein said that he is studying
the legality of the Ras Amud project before making comments on
the project. But he confirmed that the government could block
the project by invoking state security and public order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
