<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Acting Philippine Defense Chief Assumes Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary
Renato de Villa, who has already resigned to concentrate on his
presidential bid in the 1998 polls, today formally transferred his
post to Brigadier General Fortunato Abat.
</P>
<P>
Abat, a former Army chief who successfully closed peace talks
with the rebel Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) last year,
will serve in an acting capacity until after the national polls
next year.
</P>
<P>
He will concurrently head the National Disaster Coordinating
Council, which had been chaired by de Villa.
</P>
<P>
De Villa, whose resignation was accepted by President Fidel
Ramos last month, was asked by the president to stay until today
to ensure a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
At a turn-over ceremony, Ramos urged the Philippine Armed
Forces to ensure the supremacy of the constitution and the
principle of civilian authority over the military.
</P>
<P>
De Villa, who had served as defense chief since July 1991, also
reiterated an earlier call for the military to stay away from
politics.
</P>
<P>
De Villa was named to the post of defense secretary in 1991 by
the then President Corazon Aquino and was later retained in the
cabinet by President Ramos.
</P>
<P>
De Villa joined the ruling Lakas-NUCD party led by Ramos in
late July to contest for the anointment of Ramos as the party's
standard bearer in next year's elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
