<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 15:00 GMT, September 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met with Palestinian
National Authority President Yasser Arafat to discuss the Mideast
peace march in the wake of the recent U.S. peace-saving attempt,
Egypt's MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The talks were focused on evaluating the situation and
discussing means of confronting the Israeli punitive measures
imposed on the Palestinians after a series of suicide bombings in
Jerusalem. (Egypt-Arafat-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Thousands of Sierra Leoneans are fleeing the port area
of Freetown in fear of attacks by the west African peace-keeping
force known as ECOMOG, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Reports attributed the situation to ECOMOG's warning last week
to bomb the area, if Sierra Leonean troops continued its shooting
at ECOMOG aircraft. (Nigeria-S.Leoneans Flee)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The International Fund for Agricultural Development
(IFAD) and the World Food Program (WFP) signed agreements in
Beijing today to finance two comprehensive agricultural
development programs in China.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreements, the IFAD is to provide 26.53
million U.S. dollars in loans to northwest China's Qinghai
Province for a comprehensive agricultural development program, and
the WFP will provide 17.62 million dollars for a similar program
in China's Anhui Province. (China-IFAD-WFP-Agreements)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The crucial third round of Indo-Pak foreign
secretary level talks began here today to explore options to
resolve all outstanding bilateral issues, the Press Trust of India
reported.
</P>
<P>
During their second round of dialogue in Islamabad in June, the
two foreign secretaries agreed to set up eight working groups on
all outstanding issues between the two countries.
(India-Pakistan-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Four militant Muslims convicted of staging terrorist
attacks were sentenced to death and hanged by a military court
today in the country's single largest trial of Muslim extremists.
</P>
<P>
The four were among 98 Muslims, including lawyers, students and
engineers, who went on trial on July 5 on charges of attempting to
topple Egypt's secular government by unleashing a wave of terror.
(Egypt-Militants-Trial)
</P>
