<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Break State Monopoly in Telecommunication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The French government will
open seven head digits of phone numbers for lots drawing this
evening in a symbolic move to break state monopoly in the
country's telecommunication market.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the state-owned France Telecom, Cegetal
telecommunication group, Bouygues of the Italian telecommunication
group STET, and Siris, owned by the European consortium Unisource
and the U.S. giant AT&AMP;T, are competitors for the digits.
</P>
<P>
The three international private telecommunication groups have
expressed their wish that France would open its phone service
market immediately, while France Telecom has presented technical
difficulties for doing it right now.
</P>
<P>
This evening, the digits two, four, five, six, seven, eight and
nine, which are head digits of specialized numbers or long
distance and international numbers, are open for lots drawing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, France Telecom will maintain monopoly over the
digits zero, one and three, which are the respective head digits
of French domestic phone numbers, the European emergency numbers,
and video- and audio-phone service numbers.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive organ of the European
Union (EU), has authorized the competitive subscription to
telephone services within the 15-member regional alliance by the
year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
