<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Albright's Allegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran today rejected recent
allegations by the United States that Iran is the main source of
tension in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"First of all Iran is not the source of tension in the Middle
East; the presence of foreign forces and the U.S. in the region is
the source of tension," Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi
said, responding to a question posed by Xinhua, at his first press
conference since taking office on August 20.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright reportedly said last
week when she was visiting Israel that Iran is the source of
tension in the Middle East because it is seeking weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iran is, on the contrary, interested in reducing regional
tensions, and has put strengthening ties with the neighboring Arab
countries in the Gulf region in top priorities, the Iranian
foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the very presence of the U.S. forces in the Gulf would
lead to an arms race in the region.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that the U.S. has deployed about 20,000
troops and the Fifth Fleet in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Regarding recent U.S. overtures to hold talks with Iran,
Kharrazi said that Washington was not seriously seeking resumption
of ties with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the Americans are not serious in their
requests for negotiations. We are ready to negotiate only when it
is based on mutual respect, the recognition of Iran's realities
and the principle of non-interference," he added.
</P>
<P>
He further stated that the U.S. must lift its sanctions and
stop leveling allegations against Iran before any talk is
possible.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the U.S., once strategic allies, broke diplomatic
relations in 1980 after the Iranian Islamic Revolution and
U.S. hostage crisis. And the United States has been imposing
economic sanctions against Iran ever since.
</P>
<P>
"How can we talk about negotiations when all types of
sanctions are imposed on us and all types of accusations are
leveled against us?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Referring to whether setting up ties with the U.S. is against
the Islamic Revolution principles, Kharrazi said, "With the
exception of Israel that we fundamentally do not recognize, it is
not against the Islamic Revolution that we would have ties with
other countries."
</P>
<P>
Tehran would re-establish relations with Washington if it
changes its conduct, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi denied reports that the U.S. position had changed
toward Iran after some 30 million voters turned out to cast their
votes in the presidential elections on May 23.
</P>
<P>
After the elections, U.S. President Bill Clinton reportedly
called Iran a "great nation" and the landslide victory of
(President) Mohammad Khatami as a "reaffirmation of the democratic
process" in Iran.
</P>
<P>
But Kharrazi said, "I do not see any change in the positions of
the American government after the elections."
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the American media changed their stance
to Iran after the elections and put it as "a positive step."
</P>
<P>
"After the elections, we saw that the tone of the American
press on Iran had changed. This is the acceptance of a
fact ... resulting from the presence of over 30 million people in
the presidential elections," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
