<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Delegates Favor Industrialized Agriculture (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang Chuanyou, a congress delegate from a farm in northwest
China's Xinjiang, said agriculture has been regarded in China as
having good social effects but low economic performance.
In the case of industrialized agriculture, added-value of farm
produce will be increased through intensive processing.
</P>
<P>
Farmers' involvement in processing and sales will bring
increased income to them. This will compensate agriculture, and
greatly push up its economic efficiency, he said.
</P>
<P>
To promote the healthy development of industrialized
agriculture and kindle farmers' enthusiasm in this regard, many
areas have worked out relevant policies and measures, according to
delegates to the congress.
</P>
<P>
By now, the provinces of Shaanxi, Guangdong, Hunan, Hebei,
Anhui and Hubei have worked out policy documents to push ahead
with the move; Zhejiang, Yunnan and Heilongjiang have also taken
measures to support major enterprises; Shandong and Fujian are
working out related policies.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Beijing, Tianjin, Heilongjiang, Sichuan, Shandong and
Hebei are mapping out long-range development plans for
industrialized agriculture in line with their respective
agricultural development situations.
</P>
<P>
Delegates believe that industrialized agriculture, though a
gradual process, will contribute more to rural economy and even to
the entire national economic development as long as China
continues with the experiment and practice in industrialized
agriculture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
