<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Says Lebanon Track Essential to Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States' Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright today promised the U.S. will pay the
same attention to the Lebanese track as to others in the whole
Middle East peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Albright said at a joint news conference with her Lebanese
counterpart Farez Boueiz that the Lebanese track which the
U.S. supports and totally commits to is "absolutely essential" to
a comprehensive Middle East peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. must go forward to all tracks," she emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Albright held a meeting with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi,
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and Foreign Minister Boueiz prior to
the news conference.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the U.S.-Lebanese relations, Albright said that "We
have some important bilateral business and we are looking forward
to ways that the United States can assist in the recovery of
Lebanon,"
</P>
<P>
"We want to work with the Lebanese government and Lebanese
people to establish the rule of the law," she added.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz, on his part, told reporters that the role of the
U.S. as the broker in the peace talks has long been awaited.
</P>
<P>
He said that at today's meeting Lebanese leaders explained to
her the country's constant positions. "We stand for a
comprehensive and just peace in the Middle East and we look
forward to the implementation of U.N. Security Council resolutions
425 and 424," he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped Albright's visit will mean that the U.S. has really
resumed its role as the driving force for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
After the conference, Albright is going to meet Lebanese
newspapers' presidents. She will leave here for home tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Albright, on her maiden trip to the region since she took
office eight months ago in a bid to bring to life the dying
Mideast peace process, arrived here from Jordan at noon.
</P>
<P>
Short of major breakthrough, Albright said minor steps have
been achieved during her visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
