<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Central Bank Reduces Interest Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian central bank
today again reduced the interest rate of its Bank Indonesia
certificate (SBI), further easing liquidity which has so far been
tightened following recent currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The interest rates for one-week and two-week periods were
reduced by 1 percentage point, respectively from 19 percent to 18
percent and from 21 percent to 20 percent. Rates for one- and
three-month periods were cut by 2 percentage points, respectively
from 25 percent to 23 percent and from 23 percent to 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rates for overnight and six- and 12-month periods remain
respectively at 15 percent, 12.125 percent and 12.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
This is the third move by the central bank so far. The monetary
authorities have said it would reduce the rates in stages
according to the situation.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the Indonesian currency, the rupiah, at
the inter-bank spot market remained relatively stable for the day.
</P>
<P>
Until 10:00 a.m. local time, the rupiah value was recorded at
2,930/2,940 against the U.S. dollar, unchanged since Friday.
</P>
<P>
Money market dealers have not been active in making
transactions and have not responded to the central bank's move so
that the rupiah's exchange rate is still relatively stable, a
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Another factor that has prevented the dollar from rising is
that the rupiah's liquidity has been relatively tight with
inter-bank overnight interest reaching 30 to 35 percent or rising
by about 5 percent from Friday's close, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's move to reduce the interest rate for the
third time within two weeks was a follow-up to the government
reform package announced on September 3 to relax the tight
monetary policy in stages.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen more than 10 percent in the past month
and nearly 25 percent since January this year following offshore
speculative attacks on the currency and a rush by local companies
to hedge their foreign borrowings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
