<HEADLINE> Iran Seeks Closer Ties with Arab World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran declared here today it is
determined to have closer ties with the Arab countries in the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said at a press conference
"Holding ties with our neighbors is among top priorities in the
foreign affairs."
</P>
<P>
"We will seriously strive to build confidence and bring about
understanding with them," Kharrazi told foreign reporters at the
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi added that the Persian Gulf Arab countries had
modified their approach toward Iran in the aftermath of the
election of the new Iranian President Mohammad Khatami, a
moderate who favors closer ties with Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
He said, "His Excellency Mr. Khatami have very much stressed
understanding between Iran and the Persian Gulf littoral countries
and we will try to implement his policies."
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old minister who used to serve as Iran's permanent
representative to the United Nations said "The Omani and Qatari
foreign ministers have traveled to Iran and I have held a
telephone conversation with Bahraini foreign minister. All of
these are in the direction of achieving better mutual
understanding."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi welcomed the recent emergence of "a relative unity"
among the Arabs against Israel.
</P>
<P>
"A sort of awareness has emerged between Islamic and Arab
countries after the recent developments in Israel and its harsh
treatment of Palestinians and its neighboring countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, he criticized the U.S. and Qatar for planning to hold
economic conference in which Israel is scheduled to take part in
Doha, Qatar.
</P>
<P>
"We do not see it prudent that this conference would be held
at a time when Islamic world needs to be united," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is insisting on holding of this conference "because it
sees that Arab countries have formed a relative unity against
Israeli aggression," he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about relations between Iran and Iraq, Kharrazi
criticized Iraqi government for its lack of sincerity when it
announced that Iranian Shiites could go on pilgrimage to holy
cities in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Iraq did not act sincerely in announcing
that the pilgrimage to holy cities would be free," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted "This could have been done through normal channels
between the officials of the two countries, adding "This kind of
approach by Iraq has created the suspicion that Iraq probably has
hidden agenda." 
</P>
