<HEADLINE> Belgian Businessmen Urged to Invest in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Minister for Commerce
and Industry Joshua Angatia today called on Belgian businessmen
to invest in Kenya's tele-communications and energy sectors which
have been liberalized.
</P>
<P>
Opening a week-long seminar on investment, trade and tourism,
the minister said that there are also investment opportunities in
state companies which are being privatized through the sale of
government share holding.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Kenyan government is committed to ensuring
political and economic stabilities in the country which have been
considered as pre-requisites for development.
</P>
<P>
A high-powered businessmen delegation from the Francophone
Wallon region of Belgium is on a visit to Kenya with an aim to
explore possible areas of cooperation with Kenya in trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
Belgium's Francophone Wallon region is known for mechanical
electronic engineering, steel works, chemicals and glass making
with a third of its population living on export business.
</P>
<P>
Issues to be discussed at the seminar include investment,
trade and tourism opportunities, and the possibilities of using
Eldoret International Airport for cargo flights between Kenya and
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is scheduled to meet Kenyan officials in the
horticulture, power, food processing, animal feeds, iron and
steel industries and airports.
</P>
<P>
So far, nine Belgian companies have invested in Kenya in
sectors such as shipping, tele-communication, transport, clearing
and forwarding and banking.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Belgium was the third biggest importer of Kenya's
French beans and a major importer of Kenya coffee. 
</P>
