<HEADLINE> China's First Non-governmental Ecological Protection Center Set up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China's first nongovernmental
ecological protection center recently opened in Keke Sheili near
the source of the Yangtze River on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
The center, which was constructed with special cold-proofing
materials similar to those used at China's South Pole Exploratory
Station, covers a total of 3,000 sq.m. and has floor space of 80
sq m.
</P>
<P>
The center will serve as a base supporting the living and
working conditions of individuals and groups undertaking
environmental protection projects and scientific research, and as
an international academic exchange center, according to Yang Xin,
the primary benefactor of the center.
</P>
<P>
The center was jointly sponsored by over a dozen young
volunteers. Yang recently published a book on his experiences
along the river, with 200,000 yuan in profits from sales of the
book helping to fund the center.
</P>
<P>
Yang noted that three similar centers will be constructed over
the next five years, along with other centers for protecting and
treating wild animals.
</P>
<P>
Keke Sheili, located at the juncture of Qinghai Province and
the Xinjiang Uygur and Tibet autonomous regions, sits at an
elevation of over 5,000 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive study by the Chinese Academy of Sciences in
1989 revealed that the region is home to a large number of rare
animal species and a highly primitive ecological environment, as
well as an abundant array of plant and mineral products. The
report cited the region as one of the most extensive pristine
unpopulated areas in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
