<HEADLINE> Trade Conference Praises China's Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A report released today by
the UN Conference on Trade and Economic Developments (UNCAD)
points to China's success in achieving single-digit inflation,
while recording an impressive growth rate approaching 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
"This should allow Chinese policy-makers to focus attention on
structural economic deficiencies in the nation's agriculture and
infrastructure sectors," according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also noted that since 1990 the developing world has
achieved an average 4.8 percent growth when including China, and
only 3.9 percent when excluding the nation.
</P>
<P>
Li Yuefen, an economic affairs officer with UNCTAD, said that
China should place special emphasis on its service industry and
township economy in an effort to absorb surplus labor.
</P>
<P>
She also expressed the confidence that China's economy would
maintain strong growth momentum in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD, which was established in 1964 and is headquartered in
Switzerland, focuses on promoting the worldwide economy with
special emphasis placed on developing countries. China joined the
organization in 1972. 
</P>
</TEXT>
