<HEADLINE> Global Communities Urged to Clean up Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP) today called on all communities in the
world to clean up their local waterways by removing rubbish from
creeks, canals, beaches and ponds.
</P>
<P>
In a news release issued here today, the UNEP said that the
fifth annual "Clean Up the World" campaign had adopted water as
the theme for this year's event.
</P>
<P>
The campaign starting in 1993 is now emphasizing the
importance to implement "strategies to recycle and reuse waste
materials as well as to reduce waste at its source" as the
problems of waste management and the need for waste reduction are
common to communities the world over.
</P>
<P>
UNEP Executive Director Elizabeth Dowdeswell was quoted as
saying that "The Clean Up the World campaign has proven to be one of
the simplest and most effective ways of tackling these
(environmental) issues and at the same time help raise
environmental awareness."
</P>
<P>
Ian Kiernan, Founder and Chairman of Clean Up the World, noted
that as world leaders are lack of the political will to tackle the
global environmental problems as demonstrated by both earth
Summits, ordinary people must lead the way.
</P>
<P>
The annual event is scheduled to take place in more than 110
countries during 19-21 September and about 40 million people all
over the world are expected to involve in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Eight new countries have registered for this year's event,
namely Angola, El Salvador, Gabon, Madagascar, Palau, St. Kitts
and Nevis, Tanzania and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, more than 150 million people have taken part in
this global community-based movement which is one of the largest
community events ever staged in human history.
</P>
<P>
The "Clean Up the World" plans to involve every country in the
world by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
