<HEADLINE> 4 Muslim Militants Hanged After Trial in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Four militant Muslims convicted
of staging terrorist attacks were sentenced to death and hanged by
a military court today in the country's single largest trial of
Muslim extremists.
</P>
<P>
The four were among 98 Muslims, including lawyers, students and
engineers, who went on trial on July 5 on charges of attempting to
topple Egypt's secular government by unleashing a wave of terror.
</P>
<P>
They alleged to be members of the outlawed Al-Gama'a
Al-Islamiya, or the Islamic Group that launched a violent campaign
since 1992 to install a strict Islamic rule. More than 1,180
people have been killed in the violence.
</P>
<P>
The military tribunal in the Haekstep military base north of
Cairo issued life sentences against eight of the defendants and
sentenced 23 to 15 years in prison and 15 others to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Five were sentenced to seven years, eight to five years and
three to three years. All the above offenders are also sentenced
to hard labor.
</P>
<P>
Six others ended up with 10 to one-year-year imprisonment
without labor respectively.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five were acquitted and charges were dropped against one
of the defendants because he was dead.
</P>
<P>
Besides the common accusation of waging war against the
government, the accused faced additional charges including
killing police officers, nine bomb attacks on Cairo banks and
commercial centers, and participating in the 1994 assassination of
Raouf Kheiret, head of the state security department.
</P>
<P>
According to an anti-terrorism law, membership of the Islamic
Group is punishable by death, but the punishment has never been
imposed. So far, 59 extremists have been executed but for crimes
such as murder or armed attacks on banks.
</P>
<P>
Suspected Islamic militants began to be tried in military
courts in 1993, and the Haekstep court is the biggest such
facility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
