<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diversified Ownership to Pave Way for Restructuring (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new theoretical breakthrough in public sector will divert
people's attention from merely focusing on the state-owned sector
to promoting state assets and public sector.
</P>
<P>
In developing public sector, China not only should invigorate
state sector but the public sector elements in the mixed sector,
Luo Bingsheng, a delegate from the Capital Iron and Steel
Complex in Beijing, said.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough will result in the strategic
reorganization of China's state-owned firms, said Xing Bensi,
vice-president of the Party School of the CPC Central committee.
</P>
<P>
Xing said the state economic sector will retreat from some
ordinary industrial sectors so that they can concentrate on the
major industries that have a vital bearing on the lifelines of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
Another breakthrough at the current five-yearly Party congress
is the affirmation that public sector can and should take
diversified forms. And all management methods and organizational
forms that mirror the laws governing socialized production may be
utilized boldly. The congress has specially referred to developing
shareholding enterprises and joint stock enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to government sources, China started the experiment
for shareholding system in large state-owned enterprises in 1984.
By now, the number of shareholding enterprises established on the
basis of state firms has stood at a mere 900 due to some
misunderstandings about the economic system.
</P>
<P>
To expand the experiment, the Chinese government will introduce
the shareholding system and buy some shares from some enterprises
so that public capital can dominate, allocate and control more
social assets.
</P>
<P>
This will consolidate the dominant position of public sector
and state-owned economy, said Chen Huanyou, secretary of the
Jiangsu Provincial Party Committee.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that now China has listed more than 700 firms
in the domestic stock markets with more than 270 billion yuan in
capital stock.
</P>
<P>
The move benefits the re-organization of state assets so that
these enterprises can complement each other and speed up merger
and combination, said Jin Renqing, vice mayor of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Some delegates commented that shareholding is not a remedy to
treat all illness. Shi Dazhen, minister of power industry, said
the transformation through shareholding should have Chinese
characteristics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Urges EU to Take First Step to End Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran today called on
European Union (EU) and Germany in particular to take the first
step in paving the way for resuming ties with the Islamic
Republic of Iran.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said at a press conference
here that "we are hurt by what the German government did to
us. It is the responsibility of the German government to secure
our demand so that a wound which has been caused as a result of
this issue would be removed."
</P>
<P>
"The EU should look for a cure for this wound and our demand
should be fulfilled," he added in the press conference, the first
since he won the vote of confidence from the Parliament on
August 20.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi criticized the EU's decision to recall its
ambassadors to Tehran after a German court found Iranian top
leaders involved in the killing of four Kurdish Iranian
opposition leaders in the Mykonos restaurant in Berlin five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
"This issue cannot be resolved through confrontation and
unusual solidarities. The only way to resolve this would be
through political will and negotiation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ambassadors of the 15 EU countries have been absent from
Tehran since April when they were withdrawn in a protest against
Iran since the Berlin Court accused Iranian leaders of involving
in the political assassinations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Iran said later the ambassadors could return but the German
envoy must be the last to do so, a formula seen by Bonn as an
attempt to undermine EU solidarity.
</P>
<P>
European Union's special envoy Paul Meurtz came to Tehran and
held two rounds of talks with Iranian officials early this month
but he left with no progress.
</P>
<P>
At today's press conference, Kharrazi also attacked European
countries for the recent temporary ban on the importation of
Iranian pistachio into Europe.
</P>
<P>
"The pistachio ban is used as a political leverage in the
relations between Iran and Europe," he added.
</P>
<P>
The ban which will be in effect till December 15 was imposed
on Iranian pistachio after the Netherlands announced that it had
received a container of Iranian pistachio that contaminated with
fungus.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that he would be willing to meet EU foreign
ministers on the sidelines of the upcoming United Nations
General Assembly in New York this month.
</P>
<P>
"If there is any request from the European countries, and if
I feel that this would help bring about better understanding, I
will not leave their requests unanswered," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
