<HEADLINE> International Programs Help Finance China's Farm Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Fund for
Agricultural Development (IFAD) and the World Food Program (WFP),
two UN organizations, signed agreements in Beijing today to
finance two comprehensive agricultural development programs in
China.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural Minister Liu Jiang and senior Chinese officials
from agriculture, finance, foreign ministries and local government
attended the signing ceremony and a banquet afterwards for IFAD
President Fawzi Hamad Alsultan and WFP officials.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreements, IFAD is to provide 26.53 million
US dollars in loans to northwest China's Qinghai Province for a
comprehensive agricultural development program in its eastern
part, and WFP will provide 17.62 million US dollars for a similar
program in the western part of east China's Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
According to a Ministry of Agriculture official, the two areas
are economically backward and the Chinese government plans to
launch the programs to help eradicate poverty.
</P>
<P>
The official told Xinhua that the two international
organizations have helped China extensively. IFAD has promised to
provide a total of 316 million US dollars for 13 projects in
China, while WFP has offered to put 768 million US dollars in 59
projects in the country. 
</P>
