<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Military Urged to Stay away from Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami today urged the military to abstain from factional
affiliation in the political arena.
</P>
<P>
"The Armed forces have to abstain from factional politics and
do their utmost to serve the revolution," said Khatami while
speaking to the 10th gathering of the commanders and officials of
the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC).
</P>
<P>
He stated that the military commanders have to stay aloof of
the ongoing factionalism in the society and emphasized the
importance of law and order in the society and highlighted the
role of armed forces in maintaining that order.
</P>
<P>
The IRGC is an elite force in the Islamic Republic and
directly controlled by Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei. It has
about 200,000 forces in ground forces, naval forces and marines.
</P>
<P>
However, Khatami praised the country's armed forces, saying
that "the Islamic Iran relies on the its powerful and faithful
armed forces to defend its interests against the hegemonic powers
of the world."
</P>
<P>
He said that the armed forces are "humble and flexible toward
the will of the nation and sharp edged against the enemies of the
nation and revolution."
</P>
<P>
The president rejected monopoly of ideas and viewpoints in the
society and called as a "blessing" the diversity of opinions in
the political scene of the country.
</P>
<P>
Calling separation of the new generation from that of the
revolution as a threat to the revolution's survival, Khatami
expressed satisfaction over the strong bonds between the two
generations in the country.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of mobilizing the young generation
for defense of the country and called for further planning on
the national issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
