<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Shipload of Oil from Overseas Explorations Sent to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese oil tanker
carrying crude oil of the China National Oil and Gas Corporation
(CNOGC) from Peru's Talara oilfield arrived at Qinhuangdao Port in
north China this morning.
</P>
<P>
This is the first shipment since China started oil development
in foreign countries in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Huang Yan, deputy manager of CNOGC, said that global oil and
gas reserves are unevenly distributed and countries which lack
petroleum usually have to import petroleum or get involved in
exploration and development of oil resources in other countries
and then share the production with the owners.
</P>
<P>
China's annual oil and gas demand has grown five percent
because of the rapidly growing economy, but domestic oil and gas
output has increased less than two percent a year.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, it is necessary to take part in exploration and
development in foreign land to meet some of the domestic demand
and increase technical exchanges," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
The 60,000 tons of crude, which has a market value of 70
million yuan, was obtained by providing Peru with long-term
technical service. China can produce 320,000 tons of crude oil at
the Peruvian oilfield annually.
</P>
<P>
China has had contracts on a number of oil exploration and
development projects in Peru, the Sudan, Venezuela, Canada,
Thailand, Kuwait, Turkmenistan and Russia,since 1992 when it first
started exploration of oil resources overseas.
</P>
<P>
In Kuwait, it will take part in five oil projects, which will
require a total investment of three billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview, Zhou Yongkang, General Manager of CNOGC,
said that in the next five years, China will expand its oil
exploration business, focusing on the Middle Asia, Russia, and
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, China will have a production capacity of over 20
million tons of oil abroad, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
So far, 21 Chinese provinces and autonomous regions have also
opened up to overseas oil companies. By the end of August, CNOGC
had signed 36 oil contracts with oil companies from nine
countries, for exploration on 402,800 sq km of land.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
