<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former PNG Military Commander Charged with Sedition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea's (PNG)
former military commander Jerry Singirok has been charged with
sedition over the rebellion he led against the Sandline
mercenaries in March, the Australian Associated Press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Singirok, who has been dismissed from the military, was charged
on summons last week.
</P>
<P>
He did not appear at the Waigani court house today, where his
lawyer Moses Murray applied to have the case adjourned until a
second inquiry into the 35 million US dollar Sandline contract was
completed.
</P>
<P>
PNG Prime Minister Bill Skate gave an undertaking in July that
all charges against soldiers involved in the rebellion would be
withheld pending the outcome of the new inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Magistrate David Rea refused Murray's application today and
adjourned the case until September 26.
</P>
<P>
The magistrate also said Singirok must make a personal
appearance at the court, otherwise he would issue a warrant for
his arrest.
</P>
<P>
Singirok, former brigadier-general, launched a military mutiny
on March 17 against the deal to use foreign mercenaries to put
down a nine-year separatist uprising in Bougainville, an island in
PNG.
</P>
<P>
He labeled the contract "corrupt" and accused politicians and
bureaucrats of benefiting personally from it.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks of civil and military unrest followed, forcing then
Prime Minister Julius Chan and two ministers to stand aside from
office while an inquiry was held into the deal.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the inquiry cleared the Chan administration of
any corruption allegation and said Singirok was closely involved
in planning the mercenary strike against rebel leaders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Scores Nigerian Economy Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank, in this year's
edition of its assessment of the world economy, has given Nigeria a low
score, the Guardian newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
In its report titled Global Economic Prospects and the Development
Countries, the World bank says the per capita income for Nigeria has been
dwindling in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the figure was 250 U.S. dollars. But a year later, the
figure dropped by 0.7 percent to 215 dollars. A further drop of 0.8
percent is estimated for 1996.
</P>
<P>
It acknowledges that "High oil prices over the past two years
allowed (Nigeria) a swing from budget deficits averaging 12 percent of
GDP (gross domestic product) in 1990-94 to likely surpluses in
1996-97."
</P>
<P>
However, as "there are few signs of significant improvements in
fundamental policies", the bank says Nigeria and other large economies
in Africa "continue to face significant policy challenges".
</P>
<P>
"Government controls over interest rates and a dual exchange rate
system (which subsidises dollars for government use at one-fourth the
price for private market) remain in place, while progress on
privatization or public sector reform has slowed significantly", the
bank says.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, of the three billion dollars of foreign
direct investment flowing into Africa annualy between 1994 and 1995,
two billion dollars came into Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
But the bank observes that most of the fund has gone into oil and
oil-related fields in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Except for Nigeria and South Africa, the bank projects an aggregate
growth rate of "a little more than four percent a year for the coming
decade" for sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The challenge for African and other developing countries, the bank
says, "is to establish conditions that help attract more global
production and realise more of its benefits."
</P>
<P>
Such include "political and macro-economic stability, open trade
and investment regimes, improvement in transport and communications
infrastructure, adequate protection of property rights and a
predictable institutional environment without excessive red tape."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
