<HEADLINE> Dhaka Gets Access to Global Environment Facility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has for the first
time got access to the Global Environment Fund (GEF) through a
project on coastal and wetland biodiversity management, national
news agency Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha (BSS) reported here today.
</P>
<P>
A preparatory assistance document on the project was signed
here today.
</P>
<P>
The project will initially start with a preparatory assistance
of 235,000 U.S. dollars, which will lead to a project proposal
estimated at 3 million dollars, BSS said.
</P>
<P>
The GEF was created in late 1990 by industrialized and
developing countries for projects and activities that aim to
protect the global environment, with focus on biodiversity,
climate change, international waters and ozone layer depletion.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is already participating in the global effort to
phase out ozone depletion substances through an international
project, BSS said.
</P>
<P>
The biodiversity project in Bangladesh aims to build an
innovative reserve and implement a multiple resource-use
management program for the protection and sustainable management
of natural resources in at least three priority coastal and
wetland biodiversity sites, BSS added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
