<HEADLINE> Kenyan Firms Develop Web Site for Trade via </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Two Kenyan companies are
collaborating to develop a web site that will enable the business
circle in eastern Africa to trade via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Media Street Ltd. is working with the international courier
DHL in the computer venture, the East African weekly newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Media Street's Managing Director Barney Lodge said that
www.eastafrica.com will provide an instant window, through which
exporters can display their products, and an on-line mechanism
for closing deals and collecting cash.
</P>
<P>
A commission is charged for all the sales made through the
network but no fee is levied for displaying products on the web
site.
</P>
<P>
Although using the Internet to export products does not cut
down freight costs, it lowers the cost of information
procurement, said Lodge.
</P>
<P>
DHL's role will be to provide efficient delivery services to
consumers who place orders through the net.
</P>
<P>
"We are already using the web site to export flowers by
courier and we hope to expand into other products including
coffee, tea and horticulture," said Lodge.
</P>
<P>
The idea behind the web site is not only to advertise goods
and service wares but also to educate consumers by providing
information about the production process, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
