<HEADLINE> Shell, Mobil Move to Run Nigerian Refineries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Shell and Mobil, the two
leading investors in Nigeria's oil industry, may jointly manage
two of the country's refineries in a bid to improve the
efficiency of the plants.
</P>
<P>
Towards this end, the two international oil giants are
expected to present a full technical report on the two refineries
to the minister of petroleum resources today.
</P>
<P>
The report, according to industry sources, entails the
technical auditing of the two plants to ascertain the state of
their machineries, equipment and manpower.
</P>
<P>
The Port Harcourt and Warri refineries, both in the oil
production base in southern Nigeria, have a combined capacity of
335,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
But due to the poor conditions resulted from lack of timely
maintenance, the refineries have been operating with limited
capacities for years, contributing to the frequent fuel scarcity
of the leading African oil producing country.
</P>
<P>
"If the report is accepted, Shell and Mobil will handle the
turn around maintenance (TAM) as well as manage the two
refineries," the Daily Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Constant fuel scarcity due to poor management and lack of fund
for periodical maintenance of the refineries seriously slowed
down economic activities in the country earlier this year. The
Nigerian government has to resort to the import of the fuel
products to improve supply.
</P>
<P>
The move to invite foreign companies to repair and run the
refineries is expected to boost the production of oil products in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
