<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diversified Ownership to Pave Way for Restructuring (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The new definition on public
ownership and affirmation to its diversified forms, deemed as a
breakthrough at the on-going Party congress, have pointed out the
way forward for China's economic restructuring, the development of
public sector in particular.
</P>
<P>
This view is shared by delegates to the ongoing 15th National
Party Congress which opened on September 12.
</P>
<P>
It is another emancipation of the mind following the one which
took economic construction as the center of the Party's work in
the late 1970s and the decision made at the last congress in 1992
to establish socialist market economy, the delegates said.
</P>
<P>
Disregarding the traditional understanding to take public
sector as merely the state- and collectively-owned sectors, the
current Party congress affirmed that public sector also includes
the state-owned elements in the mixed sector.
</P>
<P>
"This means the increasing market shares and diversified
economic development will not fundamentally affect the socialist
nature, although they will inevitably lead to declining shares of
state-owned sector," a delegate said.
</P>
<P>
According to the new definition, public sector accounts for
one-third of the mixed sector, which pushes China's public sector
by seven percentage points, reaching 76 percent of the country's
gross national product (GNP) in 1996. The figure means that the
public sector remains dominant in China's economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
