<HEADLINE> Arafat, Mubarak Meet in Alexandria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak met with Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat to discuss the Mideast peace march in the wake of
the recent U.S. peace-saving attempt.
</P>
<P>
Their talks were focused on evaluating the situation following
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's visit and discussing
means of confronting the Israeli punitive measures imposed on the
Palestinians after a series of suicide bombings in Jerusalem,
Egypt's MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting in the south Mediterranean city, on the
Egyptian side, were Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and the
president's political adviser Osama el-Baz.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian side were Secretary General of the PLO
Executive Committee Mahmoud Abbas, Local Government Minister Saeb
Erekat, Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabiel
Shaath.
</P>
<P>
Albright said last Friday that under her sponsorship Abbas and
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy will discuss means to move
forward the Mideast peace march in New York by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
The meeting and Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad's coming visit
to Alexandria Thursday, were arranged as Albright's first trip to
the region has taken her Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas,
Syria, Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Jordan and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Ambassador Eissa Darwish said today that Mubarak and
Al-Assad will focus on the outcome of Albright's Mideast tour,
ways to promote the Arab stance, bilateral ties, regional and
international events.
</P>
<P>
Syria and the PNA were the second and third stops of Albright's
tour, which failed to score major achievements in easing tensions
and relaunching the peace march on both tracks.
</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli negotiations were frozen since March last
year. The Israeli government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
refused to commit to the promises of its Labor predecessor to
return the Golan Heights it seized from Syria in 1967 in exchange
for peace with the Arab neighbor.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks stalled in March over a new
Jewish settlement project in traditional Arab East Jerusalem,
which the Palestinians want as their future capital. The string of
suicide bombings in Jerusalem since end of July has fueled the
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
