<HEADLINE> Sierra Leoneans Flee Freetown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Sierra Leoneans are
fleeing the port area of Freetown in fear of attacks by the west
African peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG, reports reaching here
said today.
</P>
<P>
The residents were seen streaming to other areas of the capital
city or to the hinterland, carrying their property on their heads, in
cars, buses and trucks.
</P>
<P>
Reports attributed the development to ECOMOG's warning last week to
bomb the area, if Sierra Leonean troops continued its shooting at
ECOMOG aircraft.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Force Commander Victor Malu accused the
Sierra Leonean troops of deploying anti-aircraft guns amidst civilian
population, but said this would not deter his men from attacks.
</P>
<P>
On September 7, ECOMOG aircraft dropped two bombs in the Freetown
port. One did not explode, but the other damaged a vessel docked in
the port.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG accused the vessel of bringing in arms and ammunition,
apparently violating the sanctions imposed by the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS), but Sierra Leone said there were
only rice on board.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the bombardment, the Sierra Leonean troop moved
into the port area with anti-aircraft guns and other heavy weapons.
</P>
<P>
Aliu Kamara, spokesman of the ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary
Council affirmed last week that Sierra Leonean troops fired at ECOMOG
troops but failed to bring any of them down.
</P>
<P>
He expressed disgust at ECOMOG planes flying over Sierra Leonean
territories and vowed that this will never be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
Aliu Kamara argued that ECOWAS has not right to impose sanctions or
blockade on Sierra Leone and that it can only make recommendations to
the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of ECOWAS member countries approved sanctions and blockade
on Sierra Leone at their summit ending August 30 in Abuja, to force
out the government of Major Johnny Kromah, which came to power after
the May 25 coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
