<HEADLINE> Tariff Cut Conducive to Foreign Investment in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Import and export tariff cut
will be conducive to further improving China's investment
environment and encouraging foreign investment, a senior official
of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC)
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Lowering the tariff rate will also improve China's
competitiveness in the international market, the official said.
</P>
<P>
China has announced a drop of import and export tariff rate
from 23 percent to 17 percent on average as of October 1. The
reduction will affect more than 4,800 items, or more than 73
percent of the goods subject to tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the move shows that China will make good
on President Jiang Zemin's promise to lower the tariff rate in a
large way. Jiang made the statement at the 3rd APEC Informal
Leaders Meeting in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, China has cut tariffs several times, bringing the
rate down by 60 percent in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, 1996, it readjusted its taxation policy and
canceled tax exemptions for equipment imported by foreign-funded
businesses, which increased production costs of foreign-funded
enterprises, especially hi-tech companies that need to import
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The tariff cut will help reduce production costs of
foreign-funded firms, and bring more investment into China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
