<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stands Test in Currency Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A local leading banker said
that Hong Kong has passed with an A grade in the test of Southeast
Asia's financial turmoil, in which speculative attacks have sunk
currencies in the region to record lows.
</P>
<P>
C. P. Langley, chairman of the Hong Kong Association of Banks
(HKAB) for the year of 1997, told Xinhua: "The period of turmoil
has been an excellent text whether or not 'one country, two
systems' really works,"
</P>
<P>
There were doubts about whether Hong Kong would remain in
complete control of its monetary and fiscal policies, its monetary
authority and its currency after July 1, though the Basic Law
mandates that Hong Kong and the Chinese inland areas should adopt
two financial systems within one country.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) has managed
the situation under the two systems, by itself, and in a most
competent way possible," said Langley, who is also general manager
of the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation Limited (HSBC).
</P>
<P>
"It (SAR) has stood alone, the currency has stood the test,
along with the stock market and the financial service sector as a
whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar was under pressure when international
speculators had forced the devaluation of the Thai baht,
Philippine peso, Malaysian ringgit, Indonesian rupiah and
Singapore dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), which plays the
function of the central bank in Hong Kong, immediately raised the
interest rate in local money market to tighten the liquidity, and
the Hong Kong dollar stood firm.
</P>
<P>
"That's what all we have to do," said Langley, who joined HSBC
in London 36 years ago and came to Hong Kong in 1972.
</P>
<P>
"In my view, compared with other currencies in Southeast Asia,
there was virtually no pressure at all on the Hong Kong dollar,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It was rather like that one of the mischievous boys came on
to the big lion and just gave a few probes of mischievous pattern.
The lion snarled and so they run away," said the chairman of HKAB,
a body founded by statute in which all banks in Hong Kong are
obligatory to join. "I don't think they will be back."
</P>
<P>
But Langley acknowledged that the Southeast Asian currency
crisis did produce an effect on Hong Kong by leaving broader
interest rate differential between the Hong Kong currency and the
U.S. dollar. The three-month interest rate differential once went
up to 300 basis points, and now it has fallen to 175 basis points,
still much higher than the normal level of between 40 to 50 basis
points.
</P>
<P>
"I'm confident that there is steady progress towards the normal
level," the banker said. "It is a matter of weeks rather than a
matter of months."
</P>
<P>
He added that what this turmoil has done in fact is that it
enhanced the reputation of Hong Kong as the leading international
financial center in the region.
</P>
<P>
Institutional investors are confident that fundamentals in Hong
Kong are better than anywhere else, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Gas Fields Discovered in Malaysia-Thailand Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Operators in the
Malaysia- Thailand Joint Development Area (JDA) have so far
discovered 10 gas fields out of 20 exploration wells drilled.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Deputy Chief Executive Officer of
Malaysia-Thailand Joint Authority (MTJA) Songpope Polachan at the
Association of International Petroleum Negotiators 1997 Fall
Conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the operators are being vigorously pursued to
further quantify and confirm the gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
He said that under the Production Sharing Contracts (PSCs), if
the contractors discovered hydrocarbon in commercial quantity in
the contract area, they were required to submit a development plan
to MTJA for approval before they could proceed with the works and
investment on the oil or gas field development.
</P>
<P>
Under the PSCs, for gas development, the MTJA and contractors
together are required to negotiate for the sale of natural gas to
prospective buyers on a joint-dedicated basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
JDA, which is governed by MTJA, covers an area of 7,250 square
kilometers of overlapping "Continental Shelf" claimed by Malaysia
and Thailand in the lower part of the Gulf of Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
