<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The National Secretary of the French Communist Party (PCF)
Sunday once again justified the participation by the PCF into the
government, despite criticism on the government decision to
partially privatize the France Telecom group and accept the European
single currency.
</P>
<P>
At the 67th ``Humanite Festival'' organized by the PCF this
weekend, the militants from the party showed their lack of
understanding of the government's policy which they judged too
liberal.
</P>
<P>
-- For the first time in 70 years, Britain and the Irish
Republicans are sitting around the same table for negotiations,
which are judged as ``historic'' by the Northern Irish parties. The
Irish Republican Army has definitely re-installed a ceasefire after
violating it, while its political wing, Sinn Fein, has promised in
written form to respect the pact of non-violence.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The French Communist Party National Secretary Robert Hue said
on Sunday that France now needs a relaunch of its public services
and public enterprises instead of a dismantling of them. He was
speaking at the Humanite Festival in the presence of the government
ministers from the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
-- Northern Ireland peace negotiations resumed today in Belfast
with the presence of a delegation from Sinn Fein, the political wing
of the Irish Republican Army (IRA) which is for the first time
participating in the negotiations. Two ``unionist'' parties, the
Democratic Ulster Party and the United Kingdom Unionist Party, are
boycotting the talks. British Prime Minister Tony Blair warned that
the IRA and Sinn Fein are linked, and that if the IRA resumes acts
of violence, the Sinn Fein cannot sit on the negotiation table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
