<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Welcomes Progress from Albright Mideast Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine today welcomed the little improvement of the situation in
the Mideast which came after the United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright visited Israel and some Arab countries last week.
</P>
<P>
But he described the decisions made by Israel on Sunday in order
to relax the tension with Palestinians as ``small steps''.
</P>
<P>
``We should salute the efforts by Madam Albright who has exerted
strong pressure by asking the Israeli government to change its
policy toward the Palestinians,'' said Vedrine in an interview with
Radio Europe One.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government announced on Sunday a step-by-step lifting
of the blockade of the Palestinian territories, the unblocking of
payment of some Israeli fund for the Palestinian Authorities, and a
veto against the building of a new housing project in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
``These few decisions are a beginning for correcting the
situation of extreme tension which was created before. We hope that
Madam Albright can pursue her efforts, and that France and Britain
and other European countries can join these efforts to give back the
form to this peace process,'' said Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine last Friday described the policy adopted by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu toward the Palestinians as
``catastrophic'' which had ``driven Palestinians to the level of
exasperation and despair''.
</P>
<P>
``The Israeli government, which does not really like criticism,
takes into account what was said, above all when it was said by
friends,'' Vedrine noted in the interview today.
</P>
<P>
He said that Friday's criticism of Israel, which aroused an
outcry from the Israeli government, was ``an appeal from the
heart.''
</P>
<P>
``I call a cat a cat... Madam Albright said the same thing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that if the peace process is not relaunched, the
perspective would become ``darker and darker'' for Israel and its
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
``One should continue the peace process as if there was no
terrorism, and one should fight the terrorism as if there was no
peace process,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
