<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urgent: Albright Pays Sudden Visit to Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States' Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright arrived here today, ending a
two-week-long speculation about if her peace mission will cover
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
She hadn't decided if she would visit Lebanon just hours ago
when she was in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
"There is not a final decision yet," Albright told a joint
press conference with King Hussein of Jordan, but adding "I do
understand the importance of the Lebanese track" of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon was not officially included in the secretary of state's
first Middle East tour since her taking office eight months
ago. This has provoked strong criticism by Lebanese, who said she
didn't treat Lebanon as an independent country.
</P>
<P>
During her stay here, she is expected to meet Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi and Prime Minister Rafik Hariri for
discussions on the Lebanese track of the peace process and the
increased clashes in south Lebanon for the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Albright is also expected to persuade Lebanon to drop its idea
of boycotting a regional economic summit scheduled for November in
Doha, Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has joined several other Arab countries in announcing
the boycott of the summit -- which will see the participation of
Israel -- in protest against Israel's hardline policy towards the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright's on-going mission has brought her to Israel, the
Palestinian-rule areas, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Jordan. She made a
stop-over in Cyprus before her arrival here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
