<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Involvement in Explosions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran today rebutted as
"despicable" an allegation by Israel that Tehran was involved in
recent explosions in western Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Mohammadi, spokesman for the foreign ministry, also
denied Iran's attempts to build long-range nuclear weapons alleged
by Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said that these rumors were prompted by the failure of the
Israeli regime in its expansionist policies, and the closer
relations of the Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
On developments in Algeria, he condemned the recent series of
killings of innocent people by radical elements.
</P>
<P>
He particularly denounced several attacks on mosques and the
assassination of a prayer leader, saying these acts are
anti-Islamic and will hurt the feelings of Muslims world over.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi called for arrest and punishment of the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
"Iran supports all solutions that will end the suffering and
bring peace and tranquility to the Muslim nation of Algeria," he
concluded.
</P>
<P>
The fundamentalists active in Algeria have been blamed for the
violence. About 60,000 people have been reportedly killed since
the government scrapped a general election dominated by the
radical Islamic Salvation Front in January 1992 . 
</P>
</TEXT>
