<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Likely to Lift Quotas on Kenyan Textile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A new report by a U.S.
governmental agency has given a marked boost to Kenya's campaign
to lift the quotas imposed on some of its textile exports to the
United States, the East African newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. sharply limited the number of pillowcases and certain
kinds of shirts that could be imported from Kenya in 1994 after
Kenya had been found to serve as a trans-shipment point for Asian
textile and apparel exporters seeking to evade U.S. quotas.
</P>
<P>
Now the U.S. International Trade Commission (ITC), at request
of a U.S. congressional committee reviewing a bill intended to
expand U.S.-Africa trade, has furnished evidence that can be used
to help Kenya win renewal of quota-free status for pillowcases
and shirts, said the report.
</P>
<P>
An ITC study issued last week suggested that giving Kenya
virtually unlimited access to the U.S. clothing and textile
market would have negligible impact on American producers and
workers.
</P>
<P>
Quota-free entry for all of sub-Sahara's textile-exporting
countries would cause few lost jobs and very little economic loss
for U.S. manufacturers, the ITC stated.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya's trade and apparel sector has the capacity and the
capability to regain a share of the U.S. market," the report
observed.
</P>
<P>
However, Kenya would first have to provide safeguards against
unlawful textile trans-shipments to the U.S. only then would the
pillowcase and shirt quotas be lifted, said the ITC.
</P>
<P>
Kenya had enjoyed a six-fold jump in its textile and apparel
sales to the U.S. in the three years before the imposition of
quotas.
</P>
<P>
Annual exports of these Kenyans goods to the U.S. peaked at 37
million Dollars in 1994 and fell to 28 million in 1995, the year
after the quotas took effect.
</P>
<P>
Currently Kenya still ranks as the fourth-largest sub-Saharan
textile and clothing exporter to the U.S., but its seven-percent
share of total sub-Saharan exports of such goods to the U.S. lags
far behind Mauritius's 43 percent, which represented 165 million
Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Lesotho rank second and third on this scale,
with U.S. market shares of 20 percent and 17 percent
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
