<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Vehicle Sales Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Vehicle sales in Kenya,
particularly from major franchise holders, continued to drop
sharply in August with extended weekends, holiday anxiety and
civil strife cutting selling time.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund's decision on July 31 to cut
key aid package to Kenya also dealt a blow to the motor industry,
according to a report from today's "East African".
</P>
<P>
Nearly all major players lost further ground compared to the
first quarter this year when the buoyant market has been brought
to a sedate level, according to data released by the Kenya Motor
Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
August's domestic figure of 976 sales in the eastern African
country are down by eight percent of 78 units, compared with the
1996 monthly average of 1,054 units.
</P>
<P>
Toyota led with 1,156 units sold in the first eight months of
the year in Kenya, ahead of Nissan, which sold 1,126. Isuzu is
third-placed, having registered 949 new vehicles by the end of
last month.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi from Simba Colt Motors took fourth position with
758 units sold, followed by Peugeot from Marshalls EA, which sold
702 units.
</P>
<P>
The Mercedes range of luxury cars, medium and heavy range of
trucks took joint sixth place by placing 368 new vehicles on the
Kenyan road.
</P>
<P>
Given that the macro-economic indicators in the motor industry
were initially favorable, especially with the reduction of duty
in the 1997 budget, the total vehicles sold from January to
August are fewer than expected and behind schedule, the report
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
