<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kumaratunga Arrives on State Visit to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Kumaratunga, being accompanied by a delegation of some
40 officials and businessmen, arrived here today on a four-day
state visit to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
During her visit, President Kumaratunga will hold talks with
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamed which will focus on
bilateral, regional and international issues, according to a
statement by the Malaysian foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
She will witness the signing of government to government
agreements between Sri Lanka and Malaysia, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
According to a Sri Lankan High Commission statement on the
visit, a number of memoranda of understanding will be also be
signed during her visit between the Board of Investment of Sri
Lanka (BOI) and leading private sector conglomerates in Malaysia
on projects including infrastructure development, industrial and
science parks, airport expansion and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan president is also scheduled to deliver a keynote
address entitled "Cooperation and Conformity in Globalization" at
the Institute of Diplomacy and Foreign Relations here.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga's visit is the first ever by a Sri Lankan head of
state since both countries established diplomatic relations in
1957. The last visit by a Sri Lankan head of government to
Malaysia was made by Prime Minister Dudley Senanayake in 1967.
</P>
<P>
The visit is expected to boost economic ties between Sri Lanka
and Malaysia which have shown an upward trend in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's export to Malaysia has increased sharply from 6
million U.S. dollars in 1994 to 27 million dollars in 1996 when
its imports from Malaysia amounted to about 159 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
