<HEADLINE> Dialogues on Charter Changes Start in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Presidential
Palace today started the first of a series of consultation
meetings which will also be held in 31 cities and municipalities
on proposed charter changes.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the Ramos administration claimed that such
conferences were meant to persuade the people to support charter
change moves to extend the president's term.
</P>
<P>
Palace officials denied this, adding the consultation is not
aimed at "preempting" the scheduled September 21 mass rally, in
which some 1 million people will gather to voice their anger over
amending the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The multi-sectoral dialogues will be held between September 15
and 19 and led by several cabinet members. Some 500 to 1,000
participants are expected to attend each conference.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos called for the consultation meetings on
September 3 when former president Corazon Aquino and Cardinal
Jaime Sin urged the holding of the September 21 anti-Charter
change rally.
</P>
<P>
"There is need for our people to be given the opportunity to
pause, and be informed and reflect... on the issue of charter
changes as well as our economic condition with greater sobriety,
calm and discernment," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, President Ramos' failure to clarify that he would not
seek a second term or the extension of his term is leading the
country to political instability, for which many foreign investors
have pulled their funds out of the country, fueling the sharp
devaluation of the peso.
</P>
<P>
The business community has complained that the Ramos
administration has talked too much about charter changes rather
than the development of the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
