<HEADLINE> Operation Launched to Eradicate Kenya's Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
mobilized as many as 20,000 policemen in an operation to end a
four-week violence in the tourists' resort of Mombasa and its
environs, the " East African" quoted a senior police officer as
reporting today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper quoted Japheth Mwania, who is in charge
of Coast Province police, as saying that the operation will not
end until the violence is eradicated.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan police spokesman Peter Kimanthi told the paper that "By
Monday, the security situation will have changed dramatically."
</P>
<P>
Mwania, who was transferred from Nyanza Province in an
emergency reshuffle, has set up operational headquarters at
Ukunda, one of the raiders' target areas.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that security forces had targeted four areas in
Kwale and Kilifi districts in the Coast Province where more than
60 people have been killed by armed gangsters during the past one
month.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that in an operation starting at Ukunda on
Thursday evening, the Kenyan police killed 10 suspected raiders.
</P>
<P>
Mwania is leading a combined force of the general service
Unit, one company from Gilgil, administration policemen and
members of the Flying Squad from Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Leaflets circulating in coast region have called on
non-coastals to pack up and go and more than 100,000 upcountry
dwellers in the Likoni area alone are estimated to have fled
since the violence started with armed raiders attacking Likoni
police stations on August 13.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi reiterated on Thursday the
government's intention to end the violence once for all.
</P>
<P>
Tourist hotels in the coast region have been dealt a crippling
blow by the on-going month-long orgy of violence and brutal
killings.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the country's tourism industry had lost
about 10 million U.S. Dollars due to a 50 percent drop in hotel
bookings in the past one month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
