<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Move Government Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
decided today to move the government building behind the
parliament instead of putting up a new wing for new ministers.
</P>
<P>
TVNZ reported that the new project will cost the government 160
million New Zealand dollars (101 million U.S. dollars) while
putting up a new wing only needs 94 million dollars (59 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The original plan to build a new wing to accommodate more
ministers after the formation of the new coalition government last
December has met strong opposition from the public. They accused
the government of trying to build a "palace" by spending 94
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Now the government decided to move the government building
known as the Beehive because of its shape to make room for an
expansion of the parliament building. But ironically, the cost
will rise to 160 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jim Bolger said the whole project could be
completed by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
The 11-storeyed Beehive was built in the 1970s. It now houses
all the government ministers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
