<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Medical Technique In China Helps Bone Cancer Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Doctors at Shibei Hospital
in Shanghai have cured a young osteoblastoma patient by removing
the tumor from his left tibia after intensive chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
The traditional treatment for osteoblastoma, which occurs in
young or middle-aged people and which has a high mortality rate,
is to amputate the infected part and to use chemotherapy for the
entire body. This could result in serious side effects however, or
even allow the cancer to spread.
</P>
<P>
When the 18-year-old patient was admitted to hospital, Dr. Cao
Mingjun, director of the orthopedics department, decided to use a
new medical technique with the help of other doctors to avoid
amputating his limb.
</P>
<P>
They first injected large chemical doses into the bone marrow
of the tibia to kill the cancer cells and then removed the
tumor. They put a special artificial replacement for the tibia,
which will help him live a better life.
</P>
<P>
The technique has proven to be an effective way to help ease
the pain of serious handicapping caused by amputation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Manufacturing Sector Likely to Dwindle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's manufacturing sector
might dwindle drastically by the year 2000 because of lack of
investment, Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper attributed the deteriorating situation in the
industry to the government's failure to check illegal trading
practices by some neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
It said that some foreign investors are reluctant to invest in
the local manufacturing sector because Zambia is rapidly turning
out to be a "dumping ground" for cheap goods from South Africa
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Muyunda Mate, Director of Pro-Invest Agency,
as saying on Sunday that most of the big manufacturing firms will
pull out of Zambia by the year 2000 because of the "unconducive
economic climate".
</P>
<P>
"Zambia risks to have no direct foreign investment by the turn
of the century because the government seems not to care much
about the local sector," said Mate, whose company is involved in
enticing foreign direct investment to Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the current situation would spell doom to the
local industrial sector and urged the government to counteract
and slap reasonable duty on all imported goods into the country
if local industries are to be protected.
</P>
<P>
In another related report, the paper said over 50,000 jobs
have been lost in the manufacturing sector since the
liberalization of the country's economy six years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
