<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Infection Rate to Go Up in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The rates of infection of
HIV/AIDS will peak at about 27 percent of the adult population of
Zambia next year and decline gradually to 14 percent by
the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
According to the government and United Nations report on
prospects for sustainable human development in Zambia available
here today, the rate of HIV/AIDS infection will continue to rise
rapidly towards the end of the decade and possible into the next
one.
</P>
<P>
The report said at its peak, the rate of infection will double
the estimated figure in 1995.
</P>
<P>
During 1995 alone, between 600,000 to 700,000 people were
estimated to be HIV/AIDS positive and between 40,000 and 50,000
were estimated to died from the disease.
</P>
<P>
Computer projections show that burden of AIDS and difficulties
that it brings to all aspects of life are likely to become
substantially greater in the year ahead, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Projections for the future population growth rates indicate
that the current 3.2 percent rate will decline to about 2.3
percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail today quoted leader of Zambia Congress of
Trade Unions (ZCTU) as saying at the weekend the AIDS pandemic is
threatening productivity and the survival of many companies which
are experiencing a high increase in the mortality rate of their
employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
