<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians, Jewish Settlers Clash in East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Scores of Palestinians
clashed with Jewish radicals late Sunday night in East
Jerusalem's Ras Amud, after three Jewish families moved into this
mostly Arab neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
Three Jewish families, including 15 adults and children,
moved late Sunday night into two empty houses in the
controversial neighborhood of 11,000 Palestinians and sparked
immediate protests from Palestinian residents there.
</P>
<P>
They began shouting abuses at each other. The Palestinians
dismissed the Jews as thieves to take over their houses in late
night and the Jews responded by saying that Jews had the right to
live there and would remain there.
</P>
<P>
The shouting game quickly erupted into a fist-fighting between
radicals from both sides. Some Palestinians threw stones at Jews
and smashed some of their cars. But the two groups were fastly
separated by a large number of Israeli police who were deployed to
prevent further violence.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said that the police would not act to
remove the Jewish families and would allow them to remain there,
because their entry into the houses was legal. The houses were
purchased legally by the Miami-based American businessman Irving
Moscowitz, who intends to build 70 housing units for Jews, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The three Jewish families took the action following a decision
by Israeli Interior Ministry not to block Moscowitz's housing
project. Earlier Sunday, the ministry's Construction Appeals
Committee rejected a petition by two leftist Jerusalem
Municipality councillors to demand for the revocation of the
building license to Moscowitz.
</P>
<P>
In strong reaction to the latest provocation, Palestinian
officials warned about the danger of an explosion of Arab
violence.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Husseini, Palestinian National Authority's Minister for
Jerusalem Affairs, called on Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to expel the settlers from Ras Amud and block the
building project there. He warned that the failure to do so would
lead to violence and kill what is remaining in the dormant peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli opposition Labor party leader Ehud Barak lashed out at
the action taken by the Jewish radicals by moving into the
controversial Arab neighborhood, denouncing it as a "dangerous
provocation" that caused serious harm to the chance of peace and
security in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu implied on Sunday that he would not give the
green light to the Ras Amud construction at this time when
the tension between Israel and the Palestinian side was running
high due to the prolonged deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's media adviser David Bar-Illan said that the prime
minister has the final say on approving the project and will
invoke state security or public order to block its
implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
