<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navigation On Yangtze River After River is Dammed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Yangtze River will still
be open to navigation after the Three Gorges Dam starts blocking
the river in early November, according to Chinese engineers.
</P>
<P>
The river was dammed once before for the Gezhouba water control
project in Hubei Province in the 1980s, halting navigation for
about half a year. Cargo was moved by train and passengers
travelled by changing ships.
</P>
<P>
To ensure normal navigation during the Three Gorges
construction work, engineers have devised a plan using
cofferdams. A water diversion canal and temporary ship lock will
be in use six years after the Three Gorges Dam starts stopping the
flow of Yangtze in early November. The permanent ship lock will be
responsible for ships after the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
The canal is 3,726 m. long and 350 m. wide.
</P>
<P>
Ship locks and lifts will be used for three months of the year
when the flood season begins and water flow exceeds 20,000
cu.m. per second at the dam construction site.
</P>
<P>
Engineers say that a temporary ship lock and lift are being
built on the northern bank and can move a 3,000-dwt ship quickly
cross the dam.
</P>
<P>
They say that preparations for the damming work has gone well
and an experiment with navigation on the canal was done on July
1. The canal will be put into formal operation in October. The
temporary ship lock will be put into service next April.
</P>
<P>
Departments have also started dredge work on navigation channels
near the site of the dam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shareholding Helps Increase State Assets Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Development of the
shareholding system will maintain and increase the value and raise
the efficiency of the state assets, Vice-Minister of finance Zhang
Youcai said here today.
</P>
<P>
It can consolidate the dominant position of the public
ownership and the guiding role of the state sector, said Zhang,
who is also director of the State Bureau of State Assets.
</P>
<P>
But he said the institution of the shareholding system in state
enterprises must be carried out carefully, warning against the
tendency of being impatience for quick success, violation of
operating rules and practice of fraud.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who is attending the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), told Xinhua, "If we don't
reorganize the state assets and put them in circulation, it is
impossible to solve the problem of irrational structure and
inefficiency and, worse still, the state assets will gradually be
devaluated."
</P>
<P>
Attracting and allocating social funds by expanding capital
market and taking part in developing the shareholding system and
the mixed sector, the state assets can optimize structure,
maintain their value and increase efficiency, he said, adding this
has been verified in the practices in Shanghai Municipality and
Guangdong Province, which have a large number of foreign-funded
enterprises of mixed ownership.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, Zhang said, the two places exceeded
other areas in terms of the number of state-owned enterprises, the
total value of assets, the net value, interests of state-owned
shares and the total volume of state assets.
</P>
<P>
He also warned against the possibility of loss of state assets
in the course of their circulation.
</P>
<P>
The state has promulgated three regulations and over 100 rules,
thus having basically curbed the loss of state assets.
</P>
<P>
He called for building a unified, competitive and orderly
market in the development of shareholding and joint stock
partnership systems so as to prevent the practice of "rushing
headlong into mass action."
</P>
<P>
Zhang, a housekeeper of the state assets, had full confidence
in continuing to keep the state-owned sector in a dominant
position in China.
</P>
<P>
He said that by the end of 1996, the state assets in China
totaled 6.5 trillion yuan, 330 times the figure in the early
1950s.
</P>
<P>
State assets have produced 60 percent of the state revenue and
provided 67 percent of the job opportunities in urban areas, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
