<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Adopts Liberal Policy in Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government has
adopted a liberal policy in investment, and the private sector has
been given high priority in economic development, local newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria
while meeting with a delegation from the Japanese Chamber of
Commerce and Industry, which is here to explore investment
opportunities in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The government has already set up the Law Reform Commission to
update existing laws to create a suitable investment environment,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Administrative Reform Commission has also been established
to increase efficiency of administration in a bid to remove
bottlenecks in the country, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister also said that the government has
revitalized the Board of Investment for promoting investment
facilities with emphasis on infrastructure services.
</P>
<P>
Briefing on the facilities and incentives being provided by the
government, the finance minister said that the government is
providing investors with tax holidays of 5 to 10 years in general,
 15 years for private power generation companies in particular,
and facilities for repatriation of invested capitals, profit and
dividend.
</P>
<P>
Tax exemption or royalties, technical know-how and technical
assistance fees, avoidance of double taxation, six-months multiple
visas for investors are also given to the investors, the minister
added.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi currency of taka is convertible for
international payment in the current account as well as capital
account for foreign investors, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He added that reinvestment of account of foreign investors and
reinvestment of repatriable dividend are treated as new
investment.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the finance minister highlighted the great
potentials in textiles, energy, communications, oil and gas,
ports, highways and bridges, and in agro-based industries and
labor-intensive industries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
