<HEADLINE> Burundi Military Regime Rejects Summit Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Burundi military
regime of Major Pirre Buyoya has rejected to take part in the
Arusha mediation talks on the conflicts in the country as
directed by a recent Great Lakes region summit.
</P>
<P>
Local press today quoted Buyoya as saying in Bujumbura last
week that his government will not send a delegation to attend
the talks where members of the delegation were not assured of
security.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya also reiterated objections to mediator Junius Nyerere,
saying, "I personally respect Mwalimu Nyerere, but at the
mediation process he has been gradually failing to observe
neutrality and finally appears openly one-sided."
</P>
<P>
Nyerere should work alongside with another mediator and Arusha
should no longer be the venue of the talks, Buyoya said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Great Lakes region in the summit early this
month directed the Burundi military regime to the peace talks in
Arusha or prepare to face stronger sanctions for hindering
progress towards people in that central African nation.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi political crisis which was triggered by the
assassination of the country's first elected President Melchior
Ndadaye in 1993 reached a new turn in July 1996 following a
military coup that brought Major Pierre Buyoya to power after
toppling a civilian government of President Sylvester
Ntibantunganya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
