<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Growth Predicted for Latin America, the Caribbean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Latin America and the
Caribbean countries are expected to have a 5 percent growth rate
and a record low inflation of 12 percent in 1997, the
Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The figures would represent the lowest inflation in the region
in decades and one of its strongest economic performances in the
1990s, the bank's office of chief economist said.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, Chile, Mexico, Peru and some smaller countries are
expected to have growth rates approaching or over 6 percent, while
Brazil may have about 4 percent, a little pick-up from last year's
3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The region's weighted average inflation may drop to 12 percent
this year, or a median rate of 9.5 percent, down from the average
inflation of 18.5 percent in 1996 and 27.7 percent in 1995, and a
remarkable decline from over 100 percent inflation in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income for the region would rise an estimated 3
percent during the year, the bank said, but warning reforms must
be stepped up to ensure sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in its 1997 Economic and Social Progress also Report
released today, the bank said that Latin American countries are
facing three challenges: consolidating macro-economic stability,
completing structural reforms, and substantially elevating the
level of education of its work force.
</P>
<P>
It said that only 4 percent growth would be sustainable unless
these challenges are met.
</P>
<P>
To sustain a growth rate of 5.5 percent, Latin America must
complete structural reforms, which are lagging in sectors like tax
collection, privatization, labor and judicial institutions, it
said.
</P>
<P>
If the average education of the work force is raised from 5
years to 6.8 years in the next decade, growth could be increased
by at least another percentage point and poverty significantly
reduced, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
