<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Waives Import Duty, Sales Tax on Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian
government has waived import duty and sales tax on maize imports
to encourage importation of the grain from outside the country up
to the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The facility beginning from today was announced by President
Benjamin Mkapa while addressing the nation last night.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa declared 1997/98 as a food deficit period, calling on
relief organizations and other international agencies to help the
country in checking the food shortage.
</P>
<P>
He said the country faces an imminent food shortage, needing
over 916,000 tons of cereals in 13 regions.
</P>
<P>
The president assured the businessmen that the government will
liaise with the Tanzania Harbors Autority, the Tanzania Railway
Corporation, departments of customs and health to ensure quicker
clearance of consignments and ferry them upcountry.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government will help maize importers obtain
warehouse facilities for storage of food stocks at reasonable tax
rates for a short period while making final disposal
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Mkapa said the government has prohibited the
exportation of maize.
</P>
<P>
He urged countrymen to use food sparingly, to desist from
extravagant celebrations which involve making brews that consume
cereals and legumes.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa further called on people not to be choosy on food,
especially during this period of shortage.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the food shortage to the poor methods still
dominant in the agricultural sector, noting that the country's
food supply still depends on unreliable rainfall.
</P>
<P>
He urged farmers in areas which receive short rains to start
preparing their fields early and using drought-resistant seeds.
</P>
<P>
Concerted efforts from all sectors of the population will be
needed in fighting famine, since such a situation is not
different from armed warfare, Mkapa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
