<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science, Technology Park Network In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) science and technology park network began formal
operation today.
</P>
<P>
The first APEC meeting on science and technology industrial
parks opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the three-day meeting, Song Jian, State Councilor and
Minister in charge of the State Science and Technology Commission
(SSTC), read a letter from President Jiang Zemin that said the
parks were begun more than half a century ago and have helped
commercialize, industrialize, and internationalize scientific
findings.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is sponsored by the SSTC and Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and attended by government officials, administrative
personnel of the science and technology parks, scientists at
research institutes, and business people from the 18 APEC members.
</P>
<P>
Science and technology parks in many countries have become new
areas of growth, Jiang said in the letter, adding that the network
should encourage exchanges and co-operation among member parks and
contribute to sustainable economic growth in the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also wrote inscriptions for China's first group of four
state-level high-tech parks opened to the APEC members as of today
separately. They are high-tech parks in Beijing, Suzhou, Hefei and
Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
At an informal meeting of APEC last November, Jiang proposed
that an APEC science and technology park network be set up, and
the first one was built in the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone in
Guangdong Province. So far, more than 110 high-tech parks, 53 of
them state-level, have been established across the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
