<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Farm Produce Exports Projected Higher This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports of farm
products are likely to reach 242 billion baht (6.8 billion U.S.
dollars) in value, up 8.3 percent in the baht value compared with
last year, a leading local research center predicts.
</P>
<P>
The baht's de facto depreciation since July 2 would be the main
factor contributing to the rise, the Thai Farmers Bank Research
Center says.
</P>
<P>
The export value of rubber is expected to reach 65 billion baht
(1.83 billion dollars) this year, up 2.6 percent from last year,
while exports of rubber products will be valued at 21.3 billion
baht (599 million dollars), up 12.2 percent owing to increased
orders from Japan.
</P>
<P>
The export value of vegetable and fruit will rise 7.4 percent
to 29.7 billion baht (835 million dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of frozen chickens are also expected to increase 2.4
percent to 9.2 billion baht (260 million dollars) in value.
</P>
<P>
However, the research center says that rice exports this year
are expected to be worth 50 billion baht (1.4 billion dollars),
down 1.4 percent from last year, because of competition from other
countries and the drought in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Exports of frozen shrimps are expected to value 37 billion baht
(1.04 billion dollars), down 14.8 percent as local shrimp-raising
farms are troubled by diseases.
</P>
<P>
Other products are also expected to drop, according to the
research center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
