<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stands Test in Currency Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A leading local banker said
that Hong Kong has passed with an A grade in the test of Southeast
Asia's financial turmoil, in which speculative attacks have sunk
regional currencies to record lows.
</P>
<P>
C. P. Langley, chairman of the Hong Kong Association of Banks
(HKAB) for the year of 1997, told Xinhua: "The period of turmoil
has been an excellent test of whether or not 'One Country, Two
Systems' really works."
</P>
<P>
There used to be doubts about Hong Kong's complete control of
its fiscal policies, monetary authority and currency after July 1,
though the Basic Law states that Hong Kong and the Chinese
inland areas introduce two financial systems within one country.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) has
handled the situation under the two systems, by itself, and in a
most competent way possible," said Langley, who also serves as
general manager of the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation
Ltd (HSBC).
</P>
<P>
"It (HKSAR) has stood alone, the currency has stood the test,
along with the stock market and the financial service sector as a
whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar was under pressure of devaluation, when
international speculators had devaluated the Thai baht, Philippine
peso, Malaysian ringgit, Indonesian rupiah and Singapore dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), which functions as the
"central bank" in Hong Kong, immediately raised the interest rate
in the local money market to tighten the liquidity, so that the
Hong Kong dollar could stand firm.
</P>
<P>
"That's what all we have to do," said Langley, who joined HSBC
in London 36 years ago and came to Hong Kong in 1972.
</P>
<P>
"In my view, compared with other currencies in Southeast Asia,
there was virtually no pressure at all on the Hong Kong dollar,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It was rather like that one of the mischievous boys came on
to a big lion and just gave a few probes of mischievous
pattern. The lion snarled and so they run away," said the chairman
of HKAB, a body founded by statute in which all banks in Hong
Kong are obligatory to join.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think they will be back," he noted.
</P>
<P>
But Langley acknowledged that the Southeast Asian currency
turmoil did have an effect on Hong Kong by leaving broader
interest rate differential between Hong Kong and U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The three-month interest rate differential between Hong Kong
and U.S. dollars once went up to 300 basis points, which now has
fallen to 175 basis points, still much higher than the normal
level of between 40 to 50 basis points.
</P>
<P>
"I'm confident that there is a steady progress towards the
normal level," the banker said. "It is a matter of weeks rather
than a matter of months."
</P>
<P>
He added that Hong Kong's reputation has been enhanced after
this turmoil, as a leading international financial center in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Institutional investors are confident that fundamentals in Hong
Kong are better than anywhere else, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Special Markets Being Built In Southeast China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Fuzhou, the capital of China's
Fujian province, is building five large specialized markets to
help local commerce and cater to the growing consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
One of them, a second-hand goods market built on four hectares
of land, opened for business recently in downtown Fuzhou. It
trades, appraises and stores used goods, and provides
information. The first phase of the market project cost 15 million
yuan (1.8 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second market, the Yusheng Wholesale Market, handles farm
produce, clothing, and souvenirs. The main building, a
32,000-sq.m. structure was completed recently at a cost of 45
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The third is an arts and crafts center in a garden-style,
scheduled for completion next May.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of a wholesale aquatic products market is
under way on 13.33 hectares of ground and is expected to generate
2.3 billion yuan in sales annually.
</P>
<P>
The fifth market includes expansion of a footwear center that
opened in 1994. Fuzhou Footwear City has already become the
largest store of its kind in Fujian province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
