<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank/IMF Meetings Enhance Hong Kong Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The upcoming World Bank and
International Monetary Fund (IMF) annual meetings will give Hong
Kong an opportunity to demonstrate to the world that nothing has
changed after handover and business is as usual, said a leading
local banker.
</P>
<P>
C. P. Langley, chairman of the Hong Kong Association of Banks
(HKAB) for the year of 1997, told Xinhua: "The meetings will have
a tremendously positive impact on Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
He said that earlier this year IMF reclassified Hong Kong as an
advanced economy. "They would not have done that if they had not
been confident that the structural strength of Hong Kong was a
permanent feature of the economic landscape."
</P>
<P>
"That was a vote of confidence in the future relationship
between the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) and
the inland areas of China," said Langley, who is also general
manager of the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation (HSBC).
</P>
<P>
Now the annual meetings, hosted by China in the HKSAR, mean
another very important expression of confidence in the strength,
stability and future prospects of China, and especially of HKSAR,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The annual meetings, scheduled for September 23-25, are the
most prestigious annual event in the international financial
community. More than 14,000 participants, including finance
ministers and central bank governors, government officials,
representatives of international and regional organizations,
business executives and journalists, will come for the meetings,
the first major international event in Hong Kong after July 1,
1997.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will have the opportunity to show before them what
we have said before handover has come to pass after handover,"
Langley said. "Business as usual, stability and confidence -- all
these are facts of post-handover Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
As the chairman of the HKAB for a special year, Langley has
taken it as a top priority to convince overseas investors that
essentially nothing has changed after July 1. "It takes two
aspects, business as usual and stability," he added.
</P>
<P>
He cited as an example Hong Kong's banking system that stood
well in the test of the Southeast Asia's financial turbulence,
thanks to its solid foundation and prudent management.
</P>
<P>
"In a completely free and fiercely competitive market, banks
cannot afford to adopt imprudent policies. Banks have to be
efficient, profitable and inspiring consumers' confidence," said
Langley, who has worked for HSBC since 1961 and has been in Hong
Kong for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Over 80 of the world's top 100 banks are operating in Hong
Kong, one of the highest concentrations in the globe.
</P>
<P>
General managers of the three note-issuing banks in Hong Kong
-- HSBC, Standard Chartered Bank and the Bank of China -- chair
the HKAB by rotation for one year each.
</P>
<P>
HKAB is a body founded by statute mainly for the purpose of
regulating short-term deposit interest rates. All banks in Hong
Kong are obligatory to join the association, which represents
members' views to government bodies and monitors the observance of
framework of rules.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
