<HEADLINE> Nepal Wants to Replace 1950 Indo-Nepali Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Nepal has officially
proposed to India that the 47-year-old Peace and Friendship Treaty
between them be replaced with a new one, Nepali Foreign Minister
Kamal Thapa said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon returning home Sunday from a five-day visit to
India, Thapa said: "We have told them that we need a new treaty to
replace the 1950 treaty, but we haven't yet received any response
from India."
</P>
<P>
"We haven't yet put forth any specific proposals. Rather we
have, in principle, apprised them of our stance. We didn't discuss
the treaty in detail," he told reporters at the airport.
</P>
<P>
The Himalayan kingdom has already called for a review of the
1950 treaty, saying it does not reflect the changing times.
</P>
<P>
Thapa also pointed out that security provisions of the treaty
need to be approached in a new context while the provisions
regarding national treatment which are practical should be
maintained.
</P>
<P>
India has maintained that the treaty has provisions only for
scrapping, but none for modifications.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
