<HEADLINE> Haze Continues to Shadow Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Haze caused by forest fires
continued to envelope many parts of Indonesia Sunday as people
began praying for rain in hopes of quickly doing away with a
problem that would tarnish Indonesia's image abroad, Antara news
agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
In Palangkaraya, Central Kalimantan, thousands of Muslims
gathered in the parking lot of Bank Indonesia late Sunday
afternoon to pray for rain, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The prayers said if the country failed to control the forest
fires which caused the haze, it could taint Indonesia's image
abroad since the smoke was also affecting neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
At least 300,000 hectares of forest, mostly in Sumatra and
Kalimantan, have been destroyed by fires this year.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale plantations and timber companies have been blamed
for the smoke because they persisted in using fires to clear land.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Environment Sarwono Kusumaatmadja said
earlier that the haze had reached unhealthy levels in Indonesia
and in neighboring Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
He said about 20 million people are in danger of respiratory
problems due to the thick smoke.
</P>
<P>
The haze has also caused the delay of 800 flights and at least
seven boat collisions on Central Kalimantan's Mahakam River in the
last few months.
</P>
<P>
Antara said that Tabing airport in Padang, West Sumatra, was
closed on Sunday as visibility decreased to less than one
kilometer, far below the normal 3.6 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The forest fires are no longer limited to Sumatra and
Kalimantan. Smaller fires have also flared in Sulawesi, Irian Jaya
and Java, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In North Sulawesi only, it reported, fires have destroyed more
than 11,000 hectares of forest land since early August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
