<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Percent of Japanese Over 65 Years Old </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- People aged 65 or older now
account for 15.6 percent of Japan's population and those aged 70
or above make up 10.3 percent, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The record-high figures were announced by the Management and
Coordination Agency prior to today's Respect-for-the-Aged Day.
</P>
<P>
According to the agency, the number of people over 65 has
reached 19.73 million, up 730,000 from last year, and those over
70 have exceeded the 10 percent mark for the first time after
climbing 0.4 percentage point from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of those over 65, women outnumber men by 40 percent, or 11.56
million to 8.17 million, respectively, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency, in a survey released Sunday, said nearly half of
the elderly questioned fear they will suffer from senile dementia
and will require nursing care as they grow old.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a poll conducted by the Yomiuri Shimbun, a leading
Japanese newspaper last month, also showed that a majority of the
elderly felt anxious about aging.
</P>
<P>
Aging worries affected 60.9 percent of respondents from 3,000
people polled nationwide in August, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
