<HEADLINE> Australian Press Hails China's Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Australian press today
hailed China's economic reform outlined at the 15th Congress of
the Communist Party of China (CPC), saying it would offer better
opportunities for Australian businessmen.
</P>
<P>
"The reform should lead eventually to long-term gains and bring
the prospect of better opportunities for Australian businesses
involved in the China relationship," Australia's leading newspaper
The Australian said in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that Australians should understand the
connection, because China is now our third largest trade partner
in Asia behind Japan and South Korea, and is destined to become
the world's largest economy around 2020," it said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the reforms, outlined by President Jiang Zemin in
his opening address to the congress in Beijing last Friday, as a
huge challenge, the editorial said that "in the long term,
President Jiang's proposed revamp of the state-owned sector should
help provide the conditions for sustained economic growth and job
creation."
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review, the country's leading business
newspaper, said the speeding up of the reforms would offer China a
chance to take the lead in Asian economy.
</P>
<P>
"Although the (reform) program is clearly forced by domestic
imperatives, it gives China, faster than many anticipated, an
opening to seize Asian economic leadership after the appearance of
major systemic problems in Southeast Asia and the fizzling out of
Japan's Big Bang," the review said.
</P>
<P>
It said the statement of stepping up the pace of the reform is
"ideally timed," providing a "positive setting" for forthcoming
World Bank and International Monetary Fund annual meetings in Hong
Kong and Jiang's visit to Washington late next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
