<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Kuala Lumpur Int'l Airport on Trial Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A Malaysia Airlines
(MAS) Boeing 747 aircraft touched down at the new Kuala Lumpur
International Airport (KLIA) in Sepang this morning, marking the
beginning of its basic trial operation.
</P>
<P>
The test landing was witnessed by Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and Cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
The KLIA is equipped with Total Airport Management System
(TAMS) which is a sophisticated data-sourcing and processing
system that interfaces with and integrates the various electronic
sub-systems within the KLIA, thus creating a single point for the
entire airport operations and management.
</P>
<P>
The system interfaces with and integrates 29 airport
sub-systems for crisis control, flight information display, gate
collection, card access, meteorological, air traffic management
and baggage handling.
</P>
<P>
According to Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik, the first trial
run would be followed by advance trials on December 15.
</P>
<P>
Located on a 100,000 square km site, some 50 km south of Kuala
Lumpur, the 9 billion ringgit (about 3.3 billion U.S. dollars)
KLIA, Known as an "Airport in the Forest" and "Forest in the
Airport" with landscapes surrounding the terminal and satellite
area, is expected to start commercial operations during the first
quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
The KLIA will be able to accommodate 25 million passengers
yearly upon its opening day and up to 60 million by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
It will have two main runways each measuring 4,000 meters by 60
meters.
</P>
<P>
Two car parks at the airport will have a total of 12,600 bays
and of these 6,300 bays will be for short duration parking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
