<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to See Surplus of Steel Bars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will see a glut of
1.45 million tons of steel bars this year due to the slowdown in
the construction industry.
</P>
<P>
Steel bar production this year will reach 4.96 million tons,
but consumption was expected only to be 3.51 million tons,
according to a report from the Thai commerce ministry available
today.
</P>
<P>
The price of steel bars would float in accordance with the baht
and the ministry said it would monitor closely developments of the
situation to ensure fair prices for both producers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that since 1996, all steel bar producers
had been struggling with depressed prices due to the ongoing
property slump, an oversupply and fierce price wars, and some had
been unable to shoulder the losses and ceased production.
</P>
<P>
Most steel bar producers have increased the price of their
products, ranging from 500 baht to 1,500 baht based on a rate of
31.93 baht against the U.S. dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
