<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Controling Endemic Diseases In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Ningxia
Hui Autonomous Region has managed to bring the major endemic
diseases under control.
</P>
<P>
These include iodine-deficiency, fluorosis, brucellosis, and
plague. Iodine-deficiency, which usually manifests itself in
thyroid enlargement, was a major problem in the region, said Qin
Changyu, director of the region's Endemic Disease Control
Institute.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive prevention program was launched for
heavily-stricken areas in 17 counties and the iodine-deficiency
incidence dropped from 35 percent to three percent, and 140,000
patients had been treated by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Fluorine poisoning affected 640,000 people in 480 villages. The
region has spent more than 70 million yuan (about eight million US
dollars) on water purification projects to deal with the problem
and and provides 480,000 people with low-fluorine water, Qin said.
</P>
<P>
Brucellosis is spread by infected animals or animal
products. No new cases have been reported in recent years, and no
outbreaks of plague have been reported since 1962, due to
effective prevention measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
