<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Using Psychology To Help Cancer Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Psychological help for
Chinese cancer patients has been developed by the Heilongjiang
Cancer Hospital in the northeastern province of Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
Patients who have benefited from the treatment have expressed
their gratitude. In the words of Zhang Yankun, one of the
patients, "The family-like atmosphere here helps me escape my
loneliness and fear."
</P>
<P>
Unlike the dormitory-like wards in most Chinese hospitals, the
Heilongjiang Cancer Hospital allows patients to live in groups or
in single rooms where they can cook, wash up, or hold
parties. Family members can visit them in special rooms or live
with them. And there are even patients who live at home but go to
the hospital for regular visits.
</P>
<P>
"Patients often become despondent after they're taken to
hospital and separated from their family members," says the
hospital's Dr. Chen Guangmao, "We try to make the patients feel at
home by giving them a family-like atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
Open-air dances are held in the hospital garden, and patients
watch videos or listen to music in the hospital movie room, giving
them access to forms of entertainment enjoyed by ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
A "Cancer-Defiers Club" has also been established by patients
and doctors, where patients can learn of the latest developments
in treating cancer and can discuss their own experience. This
encourages patients to co-operate more in the treatment process
and helps speed up recovery a great deal.
</P>
<P>
One young man, for example, who was suffering from liver cancer
cried a lot after entering the hospital, but a group of cancer
survivors visited him and described their experience in dealing
with cancer. The young man survived in his struggle with cancer
and joined the group.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese doctors used to fight cancer with just an operation
and medication, and psychological therapy was neglected and
patients often died an early death in loneliness and desperation,"
Dr Chen commented, noting that hospital records show that patients
here live longer than was originally expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Sino-Canadian Oilfield Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A contract on China's largest
joint on-shore oil development has been signed by the China Oil
and Gas Corporation and Canada's Pan China Energy Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Development will take place in the Kongnan block in the
southern part of the Dagang Oilfield in Hebei province. It is
expected to pump 200,000 tons of crude oil a year by the end of
the century.
</P>
<P>
Financing and technology for the development will come from Pan
China, while the Dagang Oilfield covers exploration.
</P>
<P>
The contract runs for 25 years. The cooperation zone covers
90.5 square kilometers and has oil reserves estimated at 51
million tons.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the joint development is that in this way China
can use foreign funds and technology to help Dagang improve
low-grade oilfields, according to Yu Zhuangjing, who is in charge
of the project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
