<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Day of Balloting in Bosnia Elections Going Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Balloting in Bosnia's first
post-war municipal elections has entered its second day without
major serious incidents, a spokesman for the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) said in Sarajevo today.
</P>
<P>
Polling stations opened in all municipalities, except Zepce
this morning, Spokesman David Foley said.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE initially estimated that the turnout of voters was
almost 50 percent Saturday, and OSCE officials described this as a
great success regarding the fact that the voting will last for two
days.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that only one incident took place in Mostar
overnight when a group of drunk young Croats attacked two
policemen. One of them is a Croat and the other a Muslim.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the incident was only indirectly
linked with the elections, as the attacked policemen guarded a
building where OSCE supervisors were controlling ballot boxes.
</P>
<P>
Foley said measures were also taken in the western town of
Drvar to enable the completion of the entire electoral procedure
where local electoral commissions slowed down the balloting.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that 89 percent of registered voters decided
to elect authorities of municipalities where they had lived before
the war. Such a decision has been made by 96 percent of eligible
voters in the Croat-Muslim Federation and by 80 percent of voters
in the Bosnian Serb entity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
