<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Real Shangri-la Is in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A team of Chinese experts
have concluded that Shangri-la, a mysterious and beautiful mecca,
is virtually located in the Diqing Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture
in southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Shangri-la, as described in British writer James Hilton's
classic novel "Lost Horizon" in the 1930s, was the site of forced
landing by an aircraft carrying several missionaries from
India. The missionaries found Shangri-la to be a peaceful, quiet,
and beautiful land in which human beings lived in harmony with
nature.
</P>
<P>
Shangri-la gained increasingly great fame as a result of the
best-selling book and an ensuing Hollywood movie based on the
novel. Nonetheless, the true location of Shangri-la remained a
subject of controversy throughout this century.
</P>
<P>
A team of Chinese experts, after the 6-month in-depth
investigations and studies into related materials, reached the
conclusion that "Shangri-La is, in fact, located in Diqing."
</P>
<P>
While Shangri-La is simply an English word translated from
another language, the true word Shangri-la can only be found in
Tibetan Diqing dialect meaning "an ideal place in the
imagination".
</P>
<P>
Diqing is well-known for its pyramidal snow-covered mountain
ridges and peaks, steep valleys, luxuriant grasslands, and
majestic temples, which, together with other attractive human and
natural environment, are the same as described in the book.
</P>
<P>
The Yunnan provincial government recently announced a 10-year
program of building Diqing into a major tourism venue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Xinjiang Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China Xinjiang Airlines,
based in Urumqi, capital of northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, has accepted delivery of an ATR 72-210A
aircraft produced by Aero International.
</P>
<P>
The 72-seat aircraft offers a larger capacity to cope with
typical passenger loads in China, with passenger/mile costs much
lower than for other aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang airline has announced that it will introduce an
additional four aircraft of the same type over the next year.
</P>
<P>
The new aircraft will be used for flights from Urumqi to some
domestic tourism cities throughout China, as well an a number of
cities within the region.
</P>
<P>
The China Xinjiang Airlines order represents a major
breakthrough in Aero Intl's entry into the Chinese market,
according to a company official.
</P>
<P>
The company anticipates that the potential Chinese market for
ATR 72 aircraft will reach 100 units over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
China is recognized as having one of the world's most rapidly
growing economies and will thus have a greater future need for
more aircraft to meet the demand of both business and leisure
travelers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
