<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Revises Import Tariffs on 16 Items </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' National
Economic and Development Authority, the highest policy-making
body, has approved proposals to cut the import tariffs on 16
products, Business Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Though the tariff reduction would translate into an annual
revenue loss of 149 million pesos (5 million U.S. dollars), it is
expected to lower production costs of local manufacturers,
allowing them to be more competitive in both local and
international markets, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
It said that products whose tariffs were lowered to three
percent from ten percent are nitric acid, narrow fabrics, sealed
hot plates, high inrush switches and communicators, unassembled
magnetos, unassembled distributors and ignition coils, automotive
parts and others.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the tariffs on paper, billiard accessories, essence
of chicken and bird's nest were slashed to ten percent from 20
percent as duties of bowling accessories were reduced to ten
percent from 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The tariff of lumber and unassembled lighting or visual
signaling equipment will also be cut to three percent from 20
percent and that of flavored milk to 20 percent from 30 percent.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
