<HEADLINE> Missing German, US Army Planes Might Have Collided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A German army passenger plane
which has been missing since late Saturday off Angola's western
coast might have collided in mid-air with a U.S. military
transport aircraft, a German Defense Ministry spokesman said late
this evening.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility of a collision is relatively great, but it has
not yet been confirmed," said the spokesman in an interview with
the German news network N-TV.
</P>
<P>
The German plane, a Soviet-made Tupolev 154 with 24 people on
board, was en route from Cologne, Germany, to Cape Town in South
Africa for ceremonies marking the 75th anniversary of the South
African navy.
</P>
<P>
The last radio signal received from the plane was registered
late Saturday when it was about 1,500 kilometers west of Angola.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a U.S. Air Force C-141B Starlifter transport plane
had also disappeared at about the same time and the same location
on a flight from Namibia to Ascension Island in the South
Atlantic, said South African and German air force officials.
</P>
<P>
The Starlifter, with nine people on board, took off from the
Namibian capital of Windhoek and left Namibian airspace at about
5:20 p.m. local time, said the South African air and sea rescue
service. The German plane was due to make a stopover in Windhoek
at 6:30 p.m. the same day.
</P>
<P>
The German news agency DPA quoted military sources as saying
that they had been told that U.S. espionage satellites detected a
flash in the area in question that might point to a collision.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of Defense later confirmed the
disappearance of the U.S. plane but said that it was still
premature to assume that it had collided with the German plane.
</P>
<P>
Rescue units from the United States, Germany, France and South
Africa have started a massive search for the whereabouts of the
two planes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970915.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Interactive 97 Attracts Over 20,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Over 20,000 people have
visited Telecom Interactive 97, the first global interactive
multimedia forum and exhibition, for the past week at Palexpo,
Geneva, said the International Telecommunication Union (ITU).
</P>
<P>
During the week-long show ending today, the latest benefits of
technology and how these could be used in the future to enhance
the lives of the people all over the world were demonstrated,
according to a press release issued here today by the ITU, its
organizer.
</P>
<P>
At many stands, brand-new videoconferencing facilities were
used to enable interactive discussions to take place between
people on all continents around the world, along with
demonstrations of interactive medicine, education and teleworking,
and even international chess.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow's consumer products, ranging from the latest digital
cameras, with radio-controlled facilities to upload pictures to
the World Wide Web, to futuristic wristwatch telephones were on
display at the show unlike any previous telecom exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Issues discussed at the forum include the future of the
network, education and the Internet, arts and artists in the new
info-communication society. The forum and exhibition attracted a
total of 20,819 people from some 90 countries and regions, with
government ministers and heads of international organizations
among them.
</P>
<P>
The next telecom event will be Africa Telecom 98 to be hosted
by the South African government in Johannesburg from May 4 to 10,
1998. The eighth World Telecom Exhibition and Forum, Telecom 99,
will be held in Geneva from October 10 to 17, 1999, in conjunction
with Telecom Interactive 99.
</P>
<P>
Following increased demand from the industry and the ITU
members, telecom events will increase frequency from the year
2000. For the first time, in 2000, there will be two regional
telecom events, Americas Telecom 2000 and Asia Telecom 2000. In
the year 2001, there will be Africa Telecom 2001 and Telecom
Interactive 2001, with Americas Telecom 2002 and Asia Telecom 2002
following the year after. In 2003, the ninth World
Telecommunications Exhibition and Forum will be held, in
conjunction with Telecom Interactive 2003.
</P>
<P>
From the year 2004 onwards, it is tentatively planned that all
three regional telecom events will be held together in one year,
and repeated in even-numbered years, starting with Americas
Telecom 2004, Asia Telecom 2004 and Africa Telecom 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
