<HEADLINE> US Stealth Fighter Crashes on Air Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- An F-117 stealth fighter,
performing on an air show, crashed into two houses shortly after
takeoff at the Glen Martin State Airport, Maryland, today,
injuring at least four people on the ground.
</P>
<P>
The pilot ejected safely and there were no immediate reports of
deaths in the accident at about 3:30 p.m. EDT during a performance
at the Chesapeake Bay Air Show.
</P>
<P>
The plane, carrying 11,000 pounds of fuel, crashed into the
houses on Chesapeake Bay in Baltimore's northeast suburb.
</P>
<P>
F-117 stealth fighters, armed with laser-guided bombs, were
used in the Gulf War against the most heavily defended Iraqi
targets because of their ability to evade radar and radar-guided
missiles. It has the technology that uses curved or angular
surfaces to reduce radar reflection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
